13.13440|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Larrington|first=Carolyne|authorlink=|year=1999|title=The Poetic Edda: A New Translation|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0-19-283946-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |year=2002 |chapter=Olaf, Saint |editor1-last=Lindahl |editor1-first=Carl |editor2-last=McNamara |editor2-first=John |editor3-last=Lindow |editor3-first=John |title=Medieval Folklore: A Guide to Myths, Legends, Tales, Beliefs, and Customs |location=Oxford |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780195147711 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book|last=Lindow|first=John|authorlink=John Lindow|year=1978|title=Swedish Folktales and Legends|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|isbn=0-520-03520-8|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/swedishlegendsfo00essw}}\n* {{cite book|last1=MacLeod|first1=Mindy|last2=Mees|first2=Bernard|year=2006|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hx7UigqsTKoC|title=Runic Amulets and Magic Objects|publisher=[[Boydell Press]]|isbn=1-84383-205-4|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=YN_YPQAACAAJ|title=Etymological Dictionary of Proto-Celtic|last=Matasovi\u0107|first=Ranko|date=2009|publisher=Brill|year=|isbn=9789004173361|location=|language=en|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Morris|first=Christopher G.|year=1992|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nauWlPTBcjIC&dq|title=Academic Dictionary of Science and Technology|publisher=[[Gulf Professional Publishing]]|isbn=978-0-12-200400-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Orchard|first=Andy|authorlink=Andy Orchard|year=1997|title=Dictionary of Norse Myth and Legend|publisher=[[Orion Publishing Group|Cassell]]|isbn=0-304-34520-2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5hbPHQAACAAJ|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Orel|first=Vladimir|year=2003|title=A Handbook of Germanic Etymology|publisher=[[Brill Publishers|Brill]]|isbn=9004128751|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/handbookofgerman0000orel}}\n* {{cite book|last=Reynolds|first=Richard|year=1994|title=Super Heroes: A Modern Mythology|publisher=[[University Press of Mississippi]]|isbn=0-87805-694-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Robinson|first=George W.|author-mask=Robinson, George W. (Trans.)|year=1916|url=https://archive.org/details/lifesaintbonifa01robigoog|quote=life of boniface.|title=The Life of Saint Boniface by Willibald|publisher=[[Harvard University Press]]|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Sawyer|first=Birgit|year=2003|title=The Viking-Age Rune-Stones: Custom and Commemoration in Early Medieval Scandinavia|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=0-19-820643-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Simek|first=Rudolf|authorlink=Rudolf Simek|year=2007|others=Translated by Angela Hall|title=Dictionary of Northern Mythology|publisher=[[Boydell & Brewer|D.S. Brewer]]|isbn=0-85991-513-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Thorpe|first=Benjamin|authorlink=Benjamin Thorpe|year=1851|title=Northern Mythology, Compromising the Principal Traditions and Superstitions of Scandinavia, North Germany, and the Netherlands: Compiled from Original and Other Sources: Volume II: Scandinavian Popular Traditions and Superstitions|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Q-lAAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22benjamin+thorpe%22#v=onepage&q=%22benjamin%20thorpe%22&f=false|publisher=Lumley|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Thorpe|first=Benjamin|authorlink=Benjamin Thorpe|author-mask=[[Benjamin Thorpe|Thorpe, Benjamin]] (Trans.)|year=1907|title=The Elder Edda of Saemund Sigfusson|url=https://archive.org/details/eldereddasaemun02socigoog|quote=benjamin thorpe The Elder Edda of Saemund Sigfusson.|publisher=[[Norr\u0153na Society]]|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Turville-Petre|first=E. O. G.|authorlink=Gabriel Turville-Petre|year=1964|title=Myth and Religion of the North: The Religion of Ancient Scandinavia|location=London|publisher=Weidenfeld and Nicolson|oclc=460550410|ref=harv}}\n* [[Jan de Vries (linguist)|De Vries, Jan]] (1957). ''Altgermanische Religionsgeschichte'' Volume 2. 2nd ed. (repr. 1970). Grundri\u00df der germanischen Philologie, Volume 12/II. De Gruyter. {{in lang|de}}\n* {{cite book|last=Worsaae|first=J. J. A.|authorlink=Jens Jacob Asmussen Worsaae|year=1882|url=https://archive.org/details/industrialartsof02worsiala|quote=swastika thor.|title=The Industrial Arts of Denmark|publisher=Chapman and Hall|ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*{{Commonscatinline}}\n*[http://myndir.uvic.ca/doc.htm?kwId=ThoR01 MyNDIR (My Norse Digital Image Repository)] Illustrations of {{lang|non|\u00de\u00f3rr|italic=no}} from manuscripts and early print books. Clicking on the thumbnail will give you the full image and information concerning it.\n\n{{\u00de\u00f3rr}}\n{{Norse mythology}}\n{{Anglo-SaxonPaganism}}\n{{Thor}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Thor| ]]\n[[Category:Sky and weather gods]]\n[[Category:Thunder gods]]\n[[Category:Germanic gods]]\n[[Category:Heroes in Norse myths and legends]]\n[[Category:\u00c6sir]]\n[[Category:Sons of Odin]]\n[[Category:Jovian deities]]\n", "name_user": "Leornendeealdenglisc", "label": "safe", "comment": "Jayanta is the equivalent because Indra is the king of the gods. Thor isn't the king of the gods but Odin is.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thor"}
{"title_page": "Steven Seifert", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{short description|American medical toxicologist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name             = Steven A. Seifert\n| image            = Steven Seifert.jpg\n| birth_name       = Steven Alan Seifert\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=USA}}\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1950|2|27}}\n| birth_place      = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City|New York]], U.S.A.\n| education        = [[Cornell University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])}}<br/> [[University of Cincinnati]] {{small|([[Doctor of Medicine|MD]])}}<br/>[[University of Arizona]] {{small|([[Family Medicine Internship|Certificate]])}}<br/>[[University of Colorado]] {{small|([[Fellowship in Medical Toxicology|Certificate]])}}<br/>[[University of Chicago]] {{small|([[Advanced Medical Writing and Editing|Certificate]])}}\n| occupation       = Medical toxicologist, Professor, Poison Center Medical Director, Journal editor, Musician\n| years_active     = 1976\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Steven A. Seifert''' is an American [[medical toxicologist]]. He is a professor of emergency medicine at the [[University of New Mexico]], as well as the medical director of the New Mexico Poison and Drug Information Center. Since 2017, he has also been the editor-in-chief of ''[[Clinical Toxicology]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://explore.tandfonline.com/page/med/ictx-editor-in-chief |title=Editor-in-Chief Appointment Clinical Toxicology |website=Taylor & Francis |date=2016-12-06}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nSeifert received his B.S., with Honors and with Distinction, from [[Cornell University]] in 1972 and his M.D. from the [[University of Cincinnati]] in 1976. He completed his internship in [[family medicine]] at the [[University of Arizona]], his fellowship in [[medical toxicology]] at the [[University of Colorado]] and received an advanced certificate in medical writing and editing from the [[University of Chicago]].<ref name=unm>{{Cite web |url=https://vivo.health.unm.edu/individual?uri=http%3A%2F%2Fvivo.health.unm.edu%2Findividual%2Fn5104|title=Steven A. Seifert, MD |website=University of New Mexico}} VIVO Website</ref>\n\n==Medical Career==\nAfter his initial training, Seifert practiced emergency medicine from 1977 to 2001 and was certified by the American Board of Emergency Medicine, maintaining that certification for 30 years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://journals.lww.com/em-news/blog/BreakingNews/Pages/post.aspx?PostID=311 |title=Emergency Physicians Reach Milestone  |website=Emergendcy Medicine News}}</ref> After completing his Medical Toxicology fellowship, Seifert served on the staff of the Arizona Poison and Drug Information Center in [[Tucson]], after which he served as the medical director of the Nebraska Regional Poison Center in [[Omaha]] for six years. In 2005, he developed and chaired \u201cSnakebites in the New Millennium,\u201d a progenitor meeting of the Venom Week Symposiums. He also chaired Venom Week III in 2009 and co-chaired the combined Venom Week IV/International Society on Toxinology meeting in 2012.<ref name=unm/> In 2006, under a DHHS/HRSA Grant, he was part of the team that created the web-based Antivenom Index, a resource for zoos to document their holdings of antivenoms to non-native species and for clinicians to locate those antivenoms to treat exotic envenomations.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://app1.unmc.edu/publicaffairs/todaysite/sitefiles/today_full.cfm?match=2906 |title=New web-based Antivenom Index now available |last=Vehrs |first=Kristin |website=University of Nebraska Medical Center |date=2006-08-15}}</ref> In 2007, he became the medical director of the New Mexico Poison and Drug Information Center.<ref name=unm/> He has over 200 peer-reviewed, scientific publications<ref name=unm/> and contributed numerous chapters in medical texts, including ''Goldman-Cecil Medicine'',<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://hours.library.kumc.edu/Record/236824/TOC |title=Cecil TOC |website=KUMC Library}}</ref> ''Critical Care Toxicology'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/321680205 |title=Critical Care Toxicology TOC |website=ResearchGate}}</ref> ''Conn's Current Therapy'',<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=3xNBDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT1341&lpg=PT1341&dq=conn's+current+therapy+seifert#v=onepage&q=conn's%20current%20therapy%20seifert&f=false |title=Conn's Current Therapy TOC |isbn=9780323529617 |last1=Kellerman |first1=Rick D. |last2=Bope |first2=Edward T. |date=November 10, 2017 }}</ref> ''UpToDate'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.uptodate.com/contents/evaluation-and-management-of-crotalinae-rattlesnake-water-moccasin-cottonmouth-or-copperhead-bites-in-the-united-states/contributors |title=Contributor list, UpToDate |website=UpToDate}}</ref> and ''Medical Toxicology, 3e'' ([[Lippincott Williams & Wilkins]]).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.unmc.edu/news.cfm?match=1416 |title=Poison Center medical director contributes to toxicology book |last=Spellman |first=Lisa |website=University of Nebraska Medical Center |date=2004-01-26}}</ref> He co-edited ''Clinical Toxinology in Australia, Europe and Americas'' (Springer).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.springer.com/gp/book/9789401774369 |title=SpringerBooks |website=Springer.com}}</ref> He also served on the New Mexico Prescription Drug Misuse and Overdose Prevention and Pain Management Advisory Council, from its inception in 2012 through 2018, as the statutory representative of the University of New Mexico.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.governor.state.nm.us/Prescription_Drug_Misuse_and_Overdose_Prevention.aspx |title=Advisory Council Membership |website=State of NM}}</ref>\n\n==Honors and Awards==\nSeifert is a fellow of the [[American Academy of Clinical Toxicology]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://aactox.org/fellows.cfm |title=AACT Fellows as of 2015 |website=American Academy of Clinical Toxicology}}</ref> and of the [[American College of Medical Toxicology]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://exsitewebware.com/acmt/directors.html |title=ACMT Fellow Designation |website=American College of Medical Toxicology}}</ref> He previously was elected a fellow of the [[American College of Emergency Physicians]].<ref name=unm/> He has served on the Boards of Directors of the [[American College of Medical Toxicology]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://exsitewebware.com/acmt/directors.html |title=ACMT Board of Directors |website=American College of Medical Toxicology}}</ref> the [[American Association of Poison Control Centers]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20101011005361/en/American-Association-Poison-Control-Centers-Welcomes-New |title=AAPCC Board of Directors |website=Business Wire}}</ref> and the [[North American Society of Toxinology]] (NAST),<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nastox.org/board--contact.html |title=NAST Board of Directors |website=North American Society of Toxinology}}</ref> including as NAST's inaugural Board President. In 1996 he received a J.C. Penny Golden Rule Finalist Award and a subsequent U.S. Presidential Service Award nomination for his work with victims of sexual assault.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue2/1996/05/01/100954-citizen-of-the-year-named/ |title=Citizen of the year named |website=Tucson Citizen}}</ref> He received the Distinguished Alumni Award from the [[University of Cincinnati College of Medicine]] in 2011,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://med.uc.edu/alumni/awards |title=Distinguished Alumni Award |website=University of Cincinnati College of Medicine}}</ref> the Presidential Merit Award from the [[American Academy of Clinical Toxicology]] in 2018,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mailchi.mp/clintox/2018-aaction?e=827ec9d4a0 |title=AACTion Newsletter-2018-v27-#2 |website=American Academy of Clinical Toxicology}}</ref> and the Volunteer Faculty Award of the University of New Mexico College of Pharmacy in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/pg/unmcop/posts/|title=UNM College of Pharmacy Facebook Page |website=Facebook}}</ref>\n\n==Selected peer-reviewed medical publications==\n\n* {{Cite journal \n| last1 = Seifert \n| first1 = SA. \n| last2 = Boyer \n| first2 = LV. \n| doi = 10.1067/mem.2001.113135  \n| title = Recurrence phenomena after immunoglobulin therapy for snake envenomations: Part 1. Pharmacokinetics and pharmacodynamics of immunoglobulin antivenoms and related antibodies \n| journal = Annals of Emergency Medicine \n| volume = 37 \n| issue = 2 \n| pages = 189\u2013195 \n| year = 2001 \n| pmid =  11174238 \n| pmc =\n}}\n* {{Cite journal \n| last1 = Boyer \n| first1 = LV. \n| last2 = Seifert \n| first2 = SA. \n| last3 = Cain \n| first3 = JS. \n| doi = 10.1067/mem.2001.113134 \n| title = Recurrence phenomena after immunoglobulin therapy for snake envenomations: Part 2. Guidelines for clinical management with crotaline Fab antivenom \n| journal = Annals of Emergency Medicine \n| volume = 37 \n| issue = 2 \n| pages = 196\u2013201 \n| year = 2001 \n| pmid =  11174239 \n| pmc =\n}}\n* {{Cite journal\n| last1 = Dart| first1 = RC.\n| last2 = Seifert| first2 = SA.\n| last3 = Boyer| first3 = LV.\n| display-authors=etal\n| title = A randomized multicenter trial of crotalinae polyvalent immune fab (Ovine) antivenom for the treatment for crotaline snakebite in the United States | doi = 10.1001/archinte.161.16.2030\n| journal = Archives of Internal Medicine\n| volume = 161\n| issue = 16\n| pages = 2030\u20132036\n| year = 2001\n| pmid = 11525706 \n| pmc =\n| doi-access = free\n}}\n* {{Cite journal\n| last1 = Seifert | first1 = SA.\n| last2 = Boyer | first2 = LV.\n| last3 = Benson | first3 = BE.\n| display-authors=etal\n| title = AAPCC database characterization of native US venomous snake exposures, 2001-2005 \n| doi = 10.1080/15563650902870277 \n| journal = Clinical Toxicology\n| volume = 47\n| issue = 4\n| pages = 327\u2013335\n| year = 2009\n| pmid = 19514880 \n}}\n* {{Cite journal\n| last1 = Seifert | first1 = SM.\n| last2 = Seifert | first2 = SA.\n| last3 = Schaechter | first3 = JL.\n| display-authors=etal\n| title = An analysis of energy-drink toxicity in the National Poison Data System \n| doi = 10.3109/15563650.2013.820310 \n| journal = Clinical Toxicology\n| volume = 51\n| issue = 7\n| pages = 566\u2013574\n| year = 2013\n| pmid = 23879181 \n| url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/76768f2faf017e4759a3e5b1fde8a42c7fbf2d4e\n}}\n* {{Cite journal\n| last1 = Bush | first1 = S.\n| last2 = Ruha | first2 = AM.\n| last3 = Seifert | first3 = SA.\n| display-authors=etal\n| title = Comparison of F(ab')2 versus Fab antivenom for pit viper envenomation: A prospective, blinded, multicenter, randomized clinical trial\n| doi = 10.3109/15563650.2014.974263\n| journal = Clinical Toxicology\n| volume = 53\n| issue = 1\n| pages = 37\u201345\n| year = 2015\n| pmid = 25361165\n| pmc = 4364250\n| url = https://www.mendeley.com/catalogue/comparison-fab2-versus-fab-antivenom-pit-viper-envenomation-prospective-blinded-multicenter-randomiz/\n}}\n* {{Cite journal\n| last1 = Seifert | first1 = SA.\n| last2 = Kirschner | first2 = R.\n| last3 = Martin | first3 = TG.\n| display-authors=etal\n| title = Acetaminophen concentrations prior to 4 hours of ingestion: Impact on diagnostic decision-making and treatment\n| doi = 10.3109/15563650.2015.1059942\n| journal = Clinical Toxicology\n| volume = 53\n| issue = 7\n| pages = 618\u2013623\n| year = 2015\n| pmid = 26107627\n| url = https://www.mendeley.com/catalogue/acetaminophen-concentrations-prior-4-hours-ingestion-impact-diagnostic-decisionmaking-treatment/\n}}\n\n==Other Published Work==\nSeifert has published non-medical works of scientific research, as well as humor and fiction, including: \"On Batting Order\" in the Baseball Research Journal (1994; 23: 101-105), \"Sherlock Holmes: Academic Toxicologist\" in the Baker Street Journal: An Irregular Quarterly of Sherlockiana (2001; 51, no. 1: 23-27), \"The Cheap Romantic\" in the Tucson Weekly (11/11/92), and \"For the Birds\" in Tucson Lifestyle Magazine (7/95), among others.\n\n==Music Career==\nSeifert is also a jazz, tenor saxophonist who, since 2012, has performed regularly in the \"Arts-in-Medicine\" concert series at the University of New Mexico Hospital and other venues with his combo, \"Once Again.\" <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-MO1YdlcGBk |title=Once Again covers Blue Bossa |website=YouTube}}</ref> In 2020, he became a founding member of \"The Steve Seifert Project,\" a virtual music group whose members are all named, \"Steve Seifert.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gYpZAhTYbic |title=Danny Boy - The Steve Seifert Project |website=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seifert, Steven A.}}\n[[Category:American toxicologists]]\n[[Category:University of New Mexico faculty]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Cornell University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Cincinnati College of Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:Medical journal editors]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{short description|American medical toxicologist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name             = Steven A. Seifert\n| image            = Steven Seifert.jpg\n| birth_name       = Steven Alan Seifert\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=USA}}\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1950|2|27}}\n| birth_place      = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City|New York]], U.S.A.\n| education        = [[Cornell University]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])}}<br/> [[University of Cincinnati]] {{small|([[Doctor of Medicine|MD]])}}<br/>[[University of Arizona]] {{small|([[Family Medicine Internship|Certificate]])}}<br/>[[University of Colorado]] {{small|([[Fellowship in Medical Toxicology|Certificate]])}}<br/>[[University of Chicago]] {{small|([[Advanced Medical Writing and Editing|Certificate]])}}\n| occupation       = Medical toxicologist, Professor, Poison Center Medical Director, Journal editor, Musician\n| years_active     = 1976\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Steven A. Seifert''' is an American [[medical toxicologist]]. He is a professor of emergency medicine at the [[University of New Mexico]], as well as the medical director of the New Mexico Poison and Drug Information Center. Since 2017, he has also been the editor-in-chief of ''[[Clinical Toxicology]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://explore.tandfonline.com/page/med/ictx-editor-in-chief |title=Editor-in-Chief Appointment Clinical Toxicology |website=Taylor & Francis |date=2016-12-06}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nSeifert received his B.S., with Honors and with Distinction, from [[Cornell University]] in 1972 and his M.D. from the [[University of Cincinnati]] in 1976. He completed his internship in [[family medicine]] at the [[University of Arizona]], his fellowship in [[medical toxicology]] at the [[University of Colorado]] and received an advanced certificate in medical writing and editing from the [[University of Chicago]].<ref name=unm>{{Cite web |url=https://vivo.health.unm.edu/individual?uri=http%3A%2F%2Fvivo.health.unm.edu%2Findividual%2Fn5104|title=Steven A. Seifert, MD |website=University of New Mexico}} VIVO Website</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAfter his initial training, Seifert practiced emergency medicine from 1977 to 2001 and was certified by the American Board of Emergency Medicine, maintaining that certification for 30 years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://journals.lww.com/em-news/blog/BreakingNews/Pages/post.aspx?PostID=311 |title=Emergency Physicians Reach Milestone  |website=Emergendcy Medicine News}}</ref> After completing his Medical Toxicology fellowship, Seifert served on the staff of the Arizona Poison and Drug Information Center in [[Tucson]], after which he served as the medical director of the Nebraska Regional Poison Center in [[Omaha]] for six years. In 2005, he developed and chaired \u201cSnakebites in the New Millennium,\u201d a progenitor meeting of the Venom Week Symposiums. He also chaired Venom Week III in 2009 and co-chaired the combined Venom Week IV/International Society on Toxinology meeting in 2012.<ref name=unm/> In 2006, under a DHHS/HRSA Grant, he was part of the team that created the web-based Antivenom Index, a resource for zoos to document their holdings of antivenoms to non-native species and for clinicians to locate those antivenoms to treat exotic envenomations.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://app1.unmc.edu/publicaffairs/todaysite/sitefiles/today_full.cfm?match=2906 |title=New web-based Antivenom Index now available |last=Vehrs |first=Kristin |website=University of Nebraska Medical Center |date=2006-08-15}}</ref> In 2007, he became the medical director of the New Mexico Poison and Drug Information Center.<ref name=unm/> He has over 200 peer-reviewed, scientific publications<ref name=unm/> and contributed numerous chapters in medical texts, including ''Goldman-Cecil Medicine'',<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://hours.library.kumc.edu/Record/236824/TOC |title=Cecil TOC |website=KUMC Library}}</ref> ''Critical Care Toxicology'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/321680205 |title=Critical Care Toxicology TOC |website=ResearchGate}}</ref> ''Conn's Current Therapy'',<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=3xNBDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT1341&lpg=PT1341&dq=conn's+current+therapy+seifert#v=onepage&q=conn's%20current%20therapy%20seifert&f=false |title=Conn's Current Therapy TOC |isbn=9780323529617 |last1=Kellerman |first1=Rick D. |last2=Bope |first2=Edward T. |date=November 10, 2017 }}</ref> ''UpToDate'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.uptodate.com/contents/evaluation-and-management-of-crotalinae-rattlesnake-water-moccasin-cottonmouth-or-copperhead-bites-in-the-united-states/contributors |title=Contributor list, UpToDate |website=UpToDate}}</ref> and ''Medical Toxicology, 3e'' ([[Lippincott Williams & Wilkins]]).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.unmc.edu/news.cfm?match=1416 |title=Poison Center medical director contributes to toxicology book |last=Spellman |first=Lisa |website=University of Nebraska Medical Center |date=2004-01-26}}</ref> He co-edited ''Clinical Toxinology in Australia, Europe and Americas'' (Springer).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.springer.com/gp/book/9789401774369 |title=SpringerBooks |website=Springer.com}}</ref> He also served on the New Mexico Prescription Drug Misuse and Overdose Prevention and Pain Management Advisory Council, from its inception in 2012 through 2018, as the statutory representative of the University of New Mexico.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.governor.state.nm.us/Prescription_Drug_Misuse_and_Overdose_Prevention.aspx |title=Advisory Council Membership |website=State of NM}}</ref>\n\n==Honors and Awards==\nSeifert is a fellow of the [[American Academy of Clinical Toxicology]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://aactox.org/fellows.cfm |title=AACT Fellows as of 2015 |website=American Academy of Clinical Toxicology}}</ref> and of the [[American College of Medical Toxicology]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://exsitewebware.com/acmt/directors.html |title=ACMT Fellow Designation |website=American College of Medical Toxicology}}</ref> He previously was elected a fellow of the [[American College of Emergency Physicians]].<ref name=unm/> He has served on the Boards of Directors of the [[American College of Medical Toxicology]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://exsitewebware.com/acmt/directors.html |title=ACMT Board of Directors |website=American College of Medical Toxicology}}</ref> the [[American Association of Poison Control Centers]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20101011005361/en/American-Association-Poison-Control-Centers-Welcomes-New |title=AAPCC Board of Directors |website=Business Wire}}</ref> and the [[North American Society of Toxinology]] (NAST),<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nastox.org/board--contact.html |title=NAST Board of Directors |website=North American Society of Toxinology}}</ref> including as NAST's inaugural Board President. In 1996 he received a J.C. Penny Golden Rule Finalist Award and a subsequent U.S. Presidential Service Award nomination for his work with victims of sexual assault.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue2/1996/05/01/100954-citizen-of-the-year-named/ |title=Citizen of the year named |website=Tucson Citizen}}</ref> He received the Distinguished Alumni Award from the [[University of Cincinnati College of Medicine]] in 2011,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://med.uc.edu/alumni/awards |title=Distinguished Alumni Award |website=University of Cincinnati College of Medicine}}</ref> the Presidential Merit Award from the [[American Academy of Clinical Toxicology]] in 2018,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mailchi.mp/clintox/2018-aaction?e=827ec9d4a0 |title=AACTion Newsletter-2018-v27-#2 |website=American Academy of Clinical Toxicology}}</ref> and the Volunteer Faculty Award of the University of New Mexico College of Pharmacy in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/pg/unmcop/posts/|title=UNM College of Pharmacy Facebook Page |website=Facebook}}</ref>\n\n==Selected peer-reviewed medical publications==\n\n* {{Cite journal \n| last1 = Seifert \n| first1 = SA. \n| last2 = Boyer \n| first2 = LV. \n| doi = 10.1067/mem.2001.113135  \n| title = Recurrence phenomena after immunoglobulin therapy for snake envenomations: Part 1. Pharmacokinetics and pharmacodynamics of immunoglobulin antivenoms and related antibodies \n| journal = Annals of Emergency Medicine \n| volume = 37 \n| issue = 2 \n| pages = 189\u2013195 \n| year = 2001 \n| pmid =  11174238 \n| pmc =\n}}\n* {{Cite journal \n| last1 = Boyer \n| first1 = LV. \n| last2 = Seifert \n| first2 = SA. \n| last3 = Cain \n| first3 = JS. \n| doi = 10.1067/mem.2001.113134 \n| title = Recurrence phenomena after immunoglobulin therapy for snake envenomations: Part 2. Guidelines for clinical management with crotaline Fab antivenom \n| journal = Annals of Emergency Medicine \n| volume = 37 \n| issue = 2 \n| pages = 196\u2013201 \n| year = 2001 \n| pmid =  11174239 \n| pmc =\n}}\n* {{Cite journal\n| last1 = Dart| first1 = RC.\n| last2 = Seifert| first2 = SA.\n| last3 = Boyer| first3 = LV.\n| display-authors=etal\n| title = A randomized multicenter trial of crotalinae polyvalent immune fab (Ovine) antivenom for the treatment for crotaline snakebite in the United States | doi = 10.1001/archinte.161.16.2030\n| journal = Archives of Internal Medicine\n| volume = 161\n| issue = 16\n| pages = 2030\u20132036\n| year = 2001\n| pmid = 11525706 \n| pmc =\n| doi-access = free\n}}\n* {{Cite journal\n| last1 = Seifert | first1 = SA.\n| last2 = Boyer | first2 = LV.\n| last3 = Benson | first3 = BE.\n| display-authors=etal\n| title = AAPCC database characterization of native US venomous snake exposures, 2001-2005 \n| doi = 10.1080/15563650902870277 \n| journal = Clinical Toxicology\n| volume = 47\n| issue = 4\n| pages = 327\u2013335\n| year = 2009\n| pmid = 19514880 \n}}\n* {{Cite journal\n| last1 = Seifert | first1 = SM.\n| last2 = Seifert | first2 = SA.\n| last3 = Schaechter | first3 = JL.\n| display-authors=etal\n| title = An analysis of energy-drink toxicity in the National Poison Data System \n| doi = 10.3109/15563650.2013.820310 \n| journal = Clinical Toxicology\n| volume = 51\n| issue = 7\n| pages = 566\u2013574\n| year = 2013\n| pmid = 23879181 \n| url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/76768f2faf017e4759a3e5b1fde8a42c7fbf2d4e\n}}\n* {{Cite journal\n| last1 = Bush | first1 = S.\n| last2 = Ruha | first2 = AM.\n| last3 = Seifert | first3 = SA.\n| display-authors=etal\n| title = Comparison of F(ab')2 versus Fab antivenom for pit viper envenomation: A prospective, blinded, multicenter, randomized clinical trial\n| doi = 10.3109/15563650.2014.974263\n| journal = Clinical Toxicology\n| volume = 53\n| issue = 1\n| pages = 37\u201345\n| year = 2015\n| pmid = 25361165\n| pmc = 4364250\n| url = https://www.mendeley.com/catalogue/comparison-fab2-versus-fab-antivenom-pit-viper-envenomation-prospective-blinded-multicenter-randomiz/\n}}\n* {{Cite journal\n| last1 = Seifert | first1 = SA.\n| last2 = Kirschner | first2 = R.\n| last3 = Martin | first3 = TG.\n| display-authors=etal\n| title = Acetaminophen concentrations prior to 4 hours of ingestion: Impact on diagnostic decision-making and treatment\n| doi = 10.3109/15563650.2015.1059942\n| journal = Clinical Toxicology\n| volume = 53\n| issue = 7\n| pages = 618\u2013623\n| year = 2015\n| pmid = 26107627\n| url = https://www.mendeley.com/catalogue/acetaminophen-concentrations-prior-4-hours-ingestion-impact-diagnostic-decisionmaking-treatment/\n}}\n\n==Other published work==\nSeifert has published non-medical works of scientific research, as well as humor and fiction, including: \"On Batting Order\" in the Baseball Research Journal (1994; 23: 101-105), \"Sherlock Holmes: Academic Toxicologist\" in the Baker Street Journal: An Irregular Quarterly of Sherlockiana (2001; 51, no. 1: 23-27), \"The Cheap Romantic\" in the Tucson Weekly (11/11/92), and \"For the Birds\" in Tucson Lifestyle Magazine (7/95), among others.\n\n==Music career==\nSeifert is also a jazz, tenor saxophonist who, since 2012, has performed regularly in the \"Arts-in-Medicine\" concert series at the University of New Mexico Hospital and other venues with his combo, \"Once Again.\" <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-MO1YdlcGBk |title=Once Again covers Blue Bossa |website=YouTube}}</ref> In 2020, he became a founding member of \"The Steve Seifert Project,\" a virtual music group whose members are all named, \"Steve Seifert.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gYpZAhTYbic |title=Danny Boy - The Steve Seifert Project |website=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seifert, Steven A.}}\n[[Category:American toxicologists]]\n[[Category:University of New Mexico faculty]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Cornell University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Cincinnati College of Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:Medical journal editors]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n", "name_user": "Toxdoc411", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor grammatical corrections", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steven_Seifert"}
{"title_page": "World Music (Taj Mahal album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = World Music\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Taj Mahal (musician)|Taj Mahal]]\n| cover      = World_Music_Taj_Mahal_Album.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1993\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Blues]], [[reggae]], [[world music]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Taj's Blues]]\n| prev_year  = 1992\n| next_title = [[Dancing the Blues]]\n| next_year  = 1993\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r170183}}</ref>\n| noprose   = yes\n}}\n\n'''''World Music''''' is a [[compilation album]] by [[United States|American]] [[blues]] artist [[Taj Mahal (musician)|Taj Mahal]].\n\n==Track listing==\nAll tracks composed by Taj Mahal; except where indicated\n# \"When I Feel the Sea Beneath My Soul\" - 3:06 - from ''[[Music Keeps Me Together]]'' (1975)\n# \"My Ancestors\" - 4:05 - from ''[[Music Keeps Me Together]]'' (1975)\n# \"Slave Driver\" ([[Bob Marley]]) - 2:43 - from ''[[Mo' Roots (Taj Mahal album)|Mo' Roots]]'' (1974)\n# \"West Indian Revelation\" - 6:58 - from ''[[Music Keeps Me Together]]'' (1975)\n# \"Kalimba\" - 1:39 - from ''[[Recycling The Blues & Other Related Stuff]]'' (1972)\n# \"Desperate Lover\" - 2:44 - from ''[[Mo' Roots (Taj Mahal album)|Mo' Roots]]'' (1974)\n# \"Clara (St. Kitts Woman)\" - 4:02 - from ''[[Mo' Roots (Taj Mahal album)|Mo' Roots]]'' (1974)\n# \"Cajun Waltz\" - 6:03 - from ''[[Mo' Roots (Taj Mahal album)|Mo' Roots]]'' (1974)\n# \"Roll, Turn, Spin\" - 4:45 - from ''[[Music Keeps Me Together]]'' (1975)\n# \"Johnny Too Bad\" ([[The Slickers]]) - 3:15 - from ''[[Mo' Roots (Taj Mahal album)|Mo' Roots]]'' (1974)\n# \"Brown Eyed Handsome Man\" - 3:43 - from ''[[Music Keeps Me Together]]'' (1975)\n# \"Blackjack Davey\" - 3:37 - from ''[[Mo' Roots (Taj Mahal album)|Mo' Roots]]'' (1974)\n# \"Music Keeps Me Together\" ([[Earl Lindo]]) - 3:38 - from ''[[Music Keeps Me Together]]'' (1975)\n# \"When I Feel the Sea Beneath My Soul (Reprise)\" - 3:06\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taj Mahal}}\n\n[[Category:Taj Mahal (musician) albums]]\n[[Category:1993 albums]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = World Music\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Taj Mahal (musician)|Taj Mahal]]\n| cover      = World_Music_Taj_Mahal_Album.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1993\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Blues]], [[reggae]], [[world music]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Taj's Blues]]\n| prev_year  = 1992\n| next_title = [[Dancing the Blues]]\n| next_year  = 1993\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r170183}}</ref>\n| noprose   = yes\n}}\n\n'''''World Music''''' is a [[compilation album]] by [[United States|American]] [[blues]] artist [[Taj Mahal (musician)|Taj Mahal]].\n\n==Track listing==\nAll tracks composed by Taj Mahal; except where indicated\n# \"When I Feel the Sea Beneath My Soul\" - 3:06 - from ''[[Music Keeps Me Together]]'' (1975)\n# \"My Ancestors\" - 4:05 - from ''[[Music Keeps Me Together]]'' (1975)\n# \"Slave Driver\" ([[Bob Marley]]) - 2:43 - from ''[[Mo' Roots]]'' (1974)\n# \"West Indian Revelation\" - 6:58 - from ''[[Music Keeps Me Together]]'' (1975)\n# \"Kalimba\" - 1:39 - from ''[[Recycling The Blues & Other Related Stuff]]'' (1972)\n# \"Desperate Lover\" - 2:44 - from ''[[Mo' Roots]]'' (1974)\n# \"Clara (St. Kitts Woman)\" - 4:02 - from ''[[Mo' Roots]]'' (1974)\n# \"Cajun Waltz\" - 6:03 - from ''[[Mo' Roots]]'' (1974)\n# \"Roll, Turn, Spin\" - 4:45 - from ''[[Music Keeps Me Together]]'' (1975)\n# \"Johnny Too Bad\" ([[The Slickers]]) - 3:15 - from ''[[Mo' Roots]]'' (1974)\n# \"Brown Eyed Handsome Man\" - 3:43 - from ''[[Musi