host star was discovered in 2016.\n\n=== Unconfirmed or doubtful ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;border-collapse:collapse;\" cellpadding=\"2\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#efefef;\" | Star system\n! style=\"background:#efefef;\" | Planet\n! style=\"background:#efefef;\" | [[Mass]]<br /><small>({{jupiter mass}})</small>\n! style=\"background:#efefef;\" | [[Semimajor axis]]<br /><small>([[Astronomical unit|AU]])</small>\n! style=\"background:#efefef;\" | [[Orbital period]]\n!Parameter\nRef.\n! style=\"background:#efefef;\" | Discovered\n!Discovery method\n|-\n| [[MACHO-1997-BLG-41]]\n| b\n| ~3\n| ~7\n| ?\n|\n| 1999\n|\n|-\n|[[DT Virginis]]\n|[[DT Virginis c|c]]\n|8.5 \u00b1 2.5\n|1168\n|33081<sup>\u2020</sup>\n|\n|2010\n|Imaging\n|-\n|[[Kepler-47]]\n|[[Kepler-47d|d]]\n|Unknown\n|Unknown\n|187.3\n|<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hinse|first=Tobias C.|last2=Haghighipour|first2=Nader|last3=Kostov|first3=Veselin B.|last4=Go\u017adziewski|first4=Krzysztof|date=2015-01-01|title=Predicting a Third Planet in the Kepler-47 Circumbinary System|journal=The Astrophysical Journal|language=en|volume=799|issue=1|pages=88|doi=10.1088/0004-637X/799/1/88|issn=0004-637X|bibcode=2015ApJ...799...88H|arxiv = 1409.1349 }}</ref>\n|2013\n|Transit\n|-\n|[[FW Tauri]]\n|[[FW Tauri b|b]]\n|10 \u00b1 4\n|330\n|\n|\n|2013\n|Imaging\n|}\n<sup>\u2020</sup>  Orbital period measurement in years (hand calculated [[Fermi Problem|Fermi estimate]] will show this).\n\n===A pair of planets around HD 202206 or a circumbinary planet?===\n\n[[HD 202206]] is a Sun-like star orbited by two objects, one of 17 [[Jupiter mass|Mj]] and one of 2.4 [[Jupiter mass|Mj]]. The classification of HD 202206 b as a [[brown dwarf]] or \"superplanet\" is currently unclear. The two objects could have both formed in a protoplanetary disk with the inner one becoming a superplanet, or the outer planet could have formed in a circumbinary disk.<ref name=Correia>{{cite journal|author1=Correia, A. C. M. |author2=Udry, S. |author3=Mayor, M. |author4=Laskar, J. |author5=Naef, D. |author6=Pepe, F. |author7=Queloz, D. |author8=Santos, N. C. |title=The CORALIE survey for southern extra-solar planets. XIII. A pair of planets around HD 202206 or a circumbinary planet?|journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics|volume=440|issue=2|pages=751\u2013758|year=2005|doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20042376|bibcode=2005A&A...440..751C|arxiv = astro-ph/0411512 }}</ref>\nA dynamical analysis of the system further shows a 5:1 mean motion resonance between the planet and the brown dwarf.<ref name=\"Couetdic202206\"/>\nThese observations raise the question of how this system was formed, but numerical simulations show that a planet formed in a circumbinary disk can migrate inward until it is captured in resonance.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Nelson, Richard P.|title=On the evolution of giant protoplanets forming in circumbinary discs|journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society\n|volume=345|issue=1|pages=233\u2013242|year=2003|doi=10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06929.x|bibcode=2003MNRAS.345..233N}}</ref>\n\n== Fiction ==\nCircumbinary planets are common in many [[science fiction]] stories:\n* In the ''[[Trigun]]'' series, the planet orbits a binary star system.\n* In the [[Star Wars|''Star Wars'' series]], planet [[Tatooine]] orbits in a close binary system.\n* In the series ''[[Doctor Who]]'', a binary system featured in [[The Chase (Doctor Who)|''The Chase'']].\n* In the [[Star Fox series|''Star Fox'' series]], the planets orbit Lylat and Solar (an [[List of stellar classes#Class M|M-class]] [[red dwarf]])\n* In the [[The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy|''Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy'' series]], the circumbinary planet Magrathea is described as the \"most improbable planet that ever existed\".\n* Watcher's Web (Return of the Aghyrians: Book 1) by Jansen, Patty.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book|author=Nader Haghighipour|title=Planets in Binary Star Systems|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kyf7vgv6FSYC|year=2010|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-90-481-8687-7}}\n\n{{Exoplanet}}\n\n[[Category:Types of planet]]\n[[Category:Binary stars|*]]\n[[Category:Circumbinary planets| ]]\n", "name_user": "2632cgn", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circumbinary_planet"}
{"title_page": "Madhiban", "text_new": "{{Main|Somali people}}\n{{Infobox Ethnic group|\n| group            = Madhiban\n| image            = NSRW Africa Midgan.png\n| caption          = Madhiban Somali tribe\n| popplace         = {{flagcountry|Somalia}}, {{flagcountry|Ethiopia}}, {{flagcountry|Kenya}}, {{flagcountry|Djibouti}}\n| langs            = [[Somali language|Somali]]\n| rels             = [[Islam]]\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| related_groups   = \n| total_source     = \n| rawimage         = \n| population       = Estimated 8,000-10,000\n}}\nThe '''Madhiban''' (''{{lang-so|Madhibaan}}''), also known as '''Gaboye''',<ref name=madhibanca>[http://www.refworld.org/docid/538c2cc44.html Djibouti: Situation of members of the Madhiban caste, including treatment by society and authorities; state protection and services (2003-October 2013)], UNHCR, IRB Canada (2014)</ref> are an artisanal [[caste]] among [[Somali people]].<ref name=\"Levine2014p62\">{{cite book|author=Donald N. Levine|title=Greater Ethiopia: The Evolution of a Multiethnic Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NZHeBQAAQBAJ |year=2014|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-22967-6|pages=62, 195}}</ref><ref>[\u0415. de Larajasse (1972), Somali-English and Somali-English Dictionary, Trubner, pages [https://archive.org/stream/cu31924026888820#page/n131/mode/1up 108: Midgan], 119, 134, 145, 178</ref><ref name=enogaboye>Mohamed A. Eno and Abdi M. Kusow (2014), ''Racial and Caste Prejudice in Somalia'', Journal of Somali Studies, Iowa State University Press, Volume 1, Issue 2, pages 104-106</ref> They have been mistreated by the Somali people.Their traditional hereditary occupation has been as hunters.<ref>{{cite book|author=David F. Horrobin|title=The Somali, in \"A Guide to Kenya and Northern Tanzania\"|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DnrwCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA30|year=2012|publisher=Springer |isbn=978-94-011-7129-8| pages=29\u201330}}; \u0415. de Larajasse (1972), Somali-English and Somali-English Dictionary, Trubner, page [https://archive.org/stream/cu31924026888820#page/n131/mode/1up 108]</ref><ref name=larajasse1972>\u0415. de Larajasse (1972), Somali-English and Somali-English Dictionary, Trubner, pages 108, 119, 134, 145, [https://archive.org/stream/cu31924026888820#page/n201/mode/1up 178]</ref> They are no farmers,engineers,docters etc. \n\nThey are also referred to as '''Madhibe''', an appellation which is sometimes used pejoratively.<ref>''The Middle East'', Issue 4, (Northumberland Press: 2007), p.196</ref> The Madhiban have been one of the low status castes among the [[Somalis]] for a long time only because of a fairytale that some Somali tribes believe. Madhiban\u2019s are very kind joyful people it\u2019s time they get justice for how they are mistreated in Somalia. \n\n==Distribution and names==\nThe Madhiban are a part of the Somali ethnic group found in the [[Horn of Africa]] region, particularly in modern Somalia, Ethiopia, northeastern Kenya, Djibouti and Eritrea.<ref name=madhibanca/><ref name=\"Lewis1999v\">{{cite book|last1=Lewis|first1=I. M.|title=A Pastoral Democracy: A Study of Pastoralism and Politics Among the Northern Somali of the Horn of Africa|date=1999|publisher=James Currey Publishers|isbn=0852552807|pages=7\u20138, 13\u201314|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=eK6SBJIckIsC&pg=PA14|accessdate=14 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a 1960 count, they numbered around 20,000 out of 640,000 Somalis in parts of Somalia that were within the then British Protectorate. Their numbers in other parts of Somalia and other Somali regions were unknown.<ref name=\"Lewis99\">{{cite book|last1=Lewis|first1=I.M.|title=A Pastoral Democracy: A Study of Pastoralism and Politics Among the Northern Somali of the Horn of Africa|date=1999|publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster|isbn=3825830845| pages=7, 14 with footnotes |url=https://www.google.com/books?id=yoMBQCr4LysC|accessdate=23 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe terms Madhiban, Muse Dheri, Midgan or Midgaan for this Somali caste are found in historic literature, but in modern discourse, the term Gaboye is increasingly common. This caste is distinct from the Tumal and Yibir outcast communities because each is accused of things different from each other in Somali society.<ref name=enogaboye/>\n\n==Discussion==\nThe Madhiban were historically hunters, but now engage in occupations like [[leather work]] ([[shoemaking]]). They also are the traditional circumcision performers for both males,<ref>{{cite book|author=David F. Horrobin|title=The Somali, in \"A Guide to Kenya and Northern Tanzania\"|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DnrwCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA30|year=2012|publisher=Springer |isbn=978-94-011-7129-8| pages=29\u201330}}</ref><ref>\u0415. de Larajasse (1972), Somali-English and Somali-English Dictionary, Trubner, page [https://archive.org/stream/cu31924026888820#page/n131/mode/1up 108]</ref> and females in the Somali society.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Wright | first=Jane | title=Female genital mutilation: an overview | journal=Journal of Advanced Nursing | publisher=Wiley-Blackwell | volume=24 | issue=2 | year=1996 | pages=251\u2013259 | doi=10.1046/j.1365-2648.1996.01934.x }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gallo|first1=Pia Grassivaro|last2=Tita|first2=Eleanora|last3=Viviani|first3=Franco|title=At the Roots of Ethnic Female Genital Modification: Preliminary Report, in Bodily Integrity and the Politics of Circumcision |year=2006|pages=49\u201355| publisher=Springer |doi=10.1007/978-1-4020-4916-3_4}}</ref> These professions have traditionally been considered dirty, and the Madhiban have been a part of the ''sab'' or lower [[caste]]s as opposed to the ''aji'' or upper castes.<ref name=\"Jama\">{{cite book|last1=Jama|first1=Hassan Ali|title=Who Cares about Somalia: Hassan's Ordeal ; Reflections on a Nation's Future|date=2005|publisher=Verlag Hans Schiler|isbn=3899300750|pages=97\u201398|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=lAyeNqKK7bQC|accessdate=23 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Lee Gunderson, Dennis Murphy Odo and Reginald D'Silva, the Midgan have traditionally been treated as a low caste, scorned and reviled.<ref name=\"GundersonOdo2013p98\">{{cite book|author1=Lee Gunderson|author2=Dennis Murphy Odo|author3=Reginald D'Silva|title=ESL Literacy Instruction |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nak3AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA98 |year=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-05238-6|page=98}}</ref> A Midgan-Madiban has been deemed as polluting and therefore avoided as a taboo in the Somali society.<ref name=\"GundersonOdo2013p98\"/><ref name=\"Leonard2013p255\">{{cite book|author=Thomas M. Leonard|title=Encyclopedia of the Developing World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gc2NAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA255 |year=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-20508-9|page=255}}</ref><ref>Mohamed A. Eno and Abdi M. Kusow (2014), ''Racial and Caste Prejudice in Somalia'', Journal of Somali Studies, Iowa State University Press, Volume 1, Issue 2, pages 91-92, 95-96, 108-112</ref>\n\nUnder Somalia's military administration, some Madhiban were appointed to positions within the government to promote integration. The Madhiban have since obtained wider political representation. Their general social status has also improved with the expansion of urban centers.<ref name=\"Lewis\">{{cite book|last=Lewis|first=I.M.|title=Understanding Somalia and Somaliland: Culture, History, Society|year=2008|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=0231700849|pages=8}}</ref>\n\n==Description from 1890==\nIn 1890 [[\u00c9lis\u00e9e Reclus]], in his extensive work \"The Earth and its Inhabitants: AFRICA\" (Vol. IV, South and East Africa) described the Madhiban (Midgan) as follows: <blockquote>In still greater contempt are held the Midgans, called also Rami, that is to say \"Archers,\" who are universally regarded as the lowest of the low. They worship trees and snakes, and eat all the prohibited food, such as fish, fowl, eggs, hares, and gazelles. They are also daring hunters, fearlessly attacking the lion and the elephant, whom they pierce with their poisoned arrows. Like the Yebirs, the Midgans also practise medicine, and have the reputation of being extremely clever charlatans. According to the Somali legends, the lower castes are the issue of crossings between Abyssinian women and maleficent genii, while the Midgans are of still more degraded origin, their ancestors having been the slaves of these Abyssinian women.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/earthanditsinha01keangoog \"The Earth and its Inhabitants: AFRICA\", Vol. IV, South and East Africa]. By \u00c9lys\u00e9e Reclus. Edited by A.H. Keane <small>B.A.</small>, New York, D. Appleton and Company., 1890 (page 399).</ref>.</blockquote>\n\n==Law==\nUnder the 1951 UN convention, several legal proceedings have ruled that Midgan as a low caste in Somalia are \"akin to [[Dalit]]s or the untouchables in India\".<ref name=\"D\u00f6rschner2011p398\">{{cite book|author1=Andreas Zimmermann|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jAegkL7nHioC&pg=PA398|title=The 1951 Convention Relating to the Status of Refugees and Its 1967 Protocol: A Commentary|author2=Jonas D\u00f6rschner|author3=Felix Machts|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2011|isbn=978-0-19-954251-2|page=398}}</ref>\n\n==Cognate castes in Horn of Africa==\nThe Madhiban caste is not an exception limited to the Somali ethnic group, and equivalent cognate caste is found in numerous ethnic groups in [[Horn of Africa]] and [[East Africa]].<ref name=levine57/><ref name=\"Shack1964p50\"/> According to [[Donald N. Levine|Donald Levine]] \u2013 a professor of Sociology specializing in Ethiopian and Horn of Africa studies, similar caste groups in different languages and ethnic groups have been integral part of societies of this region.<ref name=levine57>{{cite book|author=Donald N. Levine|title=Greater Ethiopia: The Evolution of a Multiethnic Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NZHeBQAAQBAJ |date=10 December 2014|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-22967-6|pages=57, 169\u2013171}}</ref> These strata have featured all the defining characteristics of caste, states Levine, characteristics such as \"endogamy, hierarchy, status, concepts of pollution, restraints on commensality, a traditional occupation and membership by birth\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Donald N. Levine|title=Greater Ethiopia: The Evolution of a Multiethnic Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NZHeBQAAQBAJ |date=10 December 2014|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-22967-6|pages=57\u201358}}</ref> In east Ethiopia ethnic groups, such as the [[Oromo people]], cognates to Somali castes have been recorded in 16th century texts, states Cornelius Jaenen.<ref>Cornelius J. Jaenen (1956), \n''The Galla or Oromo of East  Ethiopia '', Southwestern Journal of Anthropology, University of Chicago Press, Vol. 12, No. 2 (Summer, 1956), pages 171-190</ref> The table below illustrate some alternate terms for castes mirroring the Madhiban in other ethnic groups that share this region with the Somali people.<ref name=\"Levine2014p196\">{{cite book|author=Donald N. Levine|title=Greater Ethiopia: The Evolution of a Multiethnic Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NZHeBQAAQBAJ |date=10 December 2014|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-22967-6|pages=195\u2013196}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Castes equivalent to Madhiban in Horn of Africa\n! Ethnic group\n! Caste name<ref name=\"Levine2014p196\"/><ref>{{cite book|author=Sa\u00efd Amir Arjomand|title=Social Theory and Regional Studies in the Global Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nzSlAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA229|year=2014|publisher=State University of New York Press|isbn=978-1-4384-5161-9|pages=229\u2013237}}</ref>\n! Occupation\n|-\n! style=\"background: #00cc00;\" | Somali\n| style=\"background: #00cc00;\" | Midgan, Madhiban || hunters, tanners\n|-\n! [[Amhara people]]\n| Weyto, Faqi\n| hunters, tanners\n|-\n! [[Argobba people]]\n| Faqin\n| tanners\n|-\n! [[Borana people]]\n| Watta\n| hunters, tanners, potters, foragers\n|-\n! [[Gurage people]]\n| Fuga\n| hunters,<ref name=\"Shack1964p50\">{{cite journal | last=Shack | first=William A. | title=54. Notes on Occupational Castes Among the Gurage of South-West Ethiopia | journal=Man | publisher=Royal Anthropological Institute of Great Britain and Ireland | volume=64 | year=1964 | pages=50\u201352 | doi=10.2307/2797801 }}</ref> woodworkers\n|-\n! [[Janjero people]]\n| Fuga\n| hunters, potters, tanners\n|-\n! [[Kafa language|Kefa people]]\n| Manjo\n| hunters, guards\n|-\n! [[Qemant people|Kimant people]]\n| Arabinya\n| tanners\n|-\n! [[She people (Africa)|She people]]\n| Kwayeju\n| hunters\n|-\n! [[Sidama people]]\n| Awacho\n| tanners\n|}\n\n==Notable Madhiban==\n*[[Maryam Mursal]]\n\n==In America==\nIn 2009, the [[Minneapolis Police Department]] of [[Minneapolis, Minnesota]], reported that \"Madhibaan with Attitude\" was one of several Somali gangs active in the city.<ref>[https://www.cbsnews.com/news/rise-of-somali-gangs-plagues-minneapolis/ Rise of Somali Gangs Plagues Minneapolis], Associated Press (July 20, 2009).</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*Hassan Ali Jama, ''Who cares about Somalia'', (Verlag Hans Schiler: 2005)\n*I.M. Lewis, ''A pastoral democracy'', (James Currey Publishers: 1999)\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.jstor.org/stable/25653242 New Arabic Documents from Somalia], B.W. Andrzejewski, I.M. Lewis and R.S. O'Fahey (1994) \u2013 mention of Midgans in early Arabic documents\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Somalia}}\n{{Ethnic groups in Ethiopia}}\n{{Ethnic groups in Kenya}}\n{{Ethnic groups in Djibouti}}\n\n{{Somali clans}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Somali People}}\n[[Category:Cushitic-speaking peoples]]\n[[Category:Ethnic Somali people| ]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Somalia| ]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Kenya]]\n[[Category:Castes]]\n[[Category:Muslim communities in Africa]]\n", "text_old": "{{Main|Somali people}}\n{{Infobox Ethnic group|\n|group = Madhiban\n|image =NSRW Africa Midgan.png\n|caption= Madhiban Somali in 1922\n|popplace = {{flagcountry|Somalia}}, {{flagcountry|Ethiopia}}, {{flagcountry|Kenya}} \n|langs = [[Somali language|Somali]] \n|rels = [[Islam]]\n}}\nThe '''Madhiban''' (''{{lang-so|Madhibaan}}''), also known as '''Gaboye''',<ref name=madhibanca>[http://www.refworld.org/docid/538c2cc44.html Djibouti: Situation of members of the Madhiban caste, including treatment by society and authorities; state protection and services (2003-October 2013)], UNHCR, IRB Canada (2014)</ref> are an artisanal [[caste]] among [[Somali people]].<ref name=\"Levine2014p62\">{{cite book|author=Donald N. Levine|title=Greater Ethiopia: The Evolution of a Multiethnic Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NZHeBQAAQBAJ |year=2014|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-22967-6|pages=62, 195}}</ref><ref>[\u0415. de Larajasse (1972), Somali-English and Somali-English Dictionary, Trubner, pages [https://archive.org/stream/cu31924026888820#page/n131/mode/1up 108: Midgan], 119, 134, 145, 178</ref><ref name=enogaboye>Mohamed A. Eno and Abdi M. Kusow (2014), ''Racial and Caste Prejudice in Somalia'', Journal of Somali Studies, Iowa State University Press, Volume 1, Issue 2, pages 104-106</ref> They have been endogamous, and their traditional hereditary occupation has been as hunters.<ref>{{cite book|author=David F. Horrobin|title=The Somali, in \"A Guide to Kenya and Northern Tanzania\"|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DnrwCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA30|year=2012|publisher=Springer |isbn=978-94-011-7129-8| pages=29\u201330}}; \u0415. de Larajasse (1972), Somali-English and Somali-English Dictionary, Trubner, page [https://archive.org/stream/cu31924026888820#page/n131/mode/1up 108]</ref><ref name=larajasse1972>\u0415. de Larajasse (1972), Somali-English and Somali-English Dictionary, Trubner, pages 108, 119, 134, 145, [https://archive.org/stream/cu31924026888820#page/n201/mode/1up 178]</ref>\n\nThey are also referred to as '''Madhibe''', an appellation which is sometimes used pejoratively.<ref>''The Middle East'', Issue 4, (Northumberland Press: 2007), p.196</ref> The Madhiban have been one of the low status castes among the [[Somalis]], along with [[Tumal]] and others.<ref name=\"Levine2014p62\"/><ref name=\"D\u00f6rschner2011p398\">{{cite book|author1=Andreas Zimmermann|author2=Jonas D\u00f6rschner|author3=Felix Machts|title=The 1951 Convention Relating to the Status of Refugees and Its 1967 Protocol: A Commentary|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jAegkL7nHioC&pg=PA398|year=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-954251-2|page=398}}</ref><ref>JW Kirk (1904), ''THE YIBIRS AND MIDGANS OF SOMALI-LAND, THEIR TRADITIONS AND DIALECTS'', African Affairs, Oxford Journals Social Sciences, Volume 4, Issue XIII, pages 91-108</ref>\n\n==Distribution and names==\nThe Madhiban are a part of the Somali ethnic group found in the [[Horn of Africa]] region, particularly in modern Somalia, Ethiopia, northeastern Kenya, Djibouti and Eritrea.<ref name=madhibanca/><ref name=\"Lewis1999v\">{{cite book|last1=Lewis|first1=I. M.|title=A Pastoral Democracy: A Study of Pastoralism and Politics Among the Northern Somali of the Horn of Africa|date=1999|publisher=James Currey Publishers|isbn=0852552807|pages=7\u20138, 13\u201314|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=eK6SBJIckIsC&pg=PA14|accessdate=14 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a 1960 count, they numbered around 20,000 out of 640,000 Somalis in parts of Somalia that were within the then British Protectorate. Their numbers in other parts of Somalia and other Somali regions were unknown.<ref name=\"Lewis99\">{{cite book|last1=Lewis|first1=I.M.|title=A Pastoral Democracy: A Study of Pastoralism and Politics Among the Northern Somali of the Horn of Africa|date=1999|publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster|isbn=3825830845| pages=7, 14 with footnotes |url=https://www.google.com/books?id=yoMBQCr4LysC|accessdate=23 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe terms Madhiban, Muse Dheri, Midgan or Midgaan for this Somali caste are found in historic literature, but in modern discourse, the term Gaboye is increasingly common. This caste is distinct from the Tumal and Yibir outcast communities because each is accused of things different from each other in Somali society.<ref name=enogaboye/>\n\n==Discussion==\nThe Madhiban were historically hunters, but now engage in occupations like [[leather work]] ([[shoemaking]]). They also are the traditional circumcision performers for both males,<ref>{{cite book|author=David F. Horrobin|title=The Somali, in \"A Guide to Kenya and Northern Tanzania\"|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DnrwCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA30|year=2012|publisher=Springer |isbn=978-94-011-7129-8| pages=29\u201330}}</ref><ref>\u0415. de Larajasse (1972), Somali-English and Somali-English Dictionary, Trubner, page [https://archive.org/stream/cu31924026888820#page/n131/mode/1up 108]</ref> and females in the Somali society.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Wright | first=Jane | title=Female genital mutilation: an overview | journal=Journal of Advanced Nursing | publisher=Wiley-Blackwell | volume=24 | issue=2 | year=1996 | pages=251\u2013259 | doi=10.1046/j.1365-2648.1996.01934.x }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gallo|first1=Pia Grassivaro|last2=Tita|first2=Eleanora|last3=Viviani|first3=Franco|title=At the Roots of Ethnic Female Genital Modification: Preliminary Report, in Bodily Integrity and the Politics of Circumcision |year=2006|pages=49\u201355| publisher=Springer |doi=10.1007/978-1-4020-4916-3_4}}</ref> These professions have traditionally been considered dirty, and the Madhiban have been a part of the ''sab'' or lower [[caste]]s as opposed to the ''aji'' or upper castes.<ref name=\"Jama\">{{cite book|last1=Jama|first1=Hassan Ali|title=Who Cares about Somalia: Hassan's Ordeal ; Reflections on a Nation's Future|date=2005|publisher=Verlag Hans Schiler|isbn=3899300750|pages=97\u201398|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=lAyeNqKK7bQC|accessdate=23 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Lee Gunderson, Dennis Murphy Odo and Reginald D'Silva, the Midgan have traditionally been treated as a low caste, scorned and reviled.<ref name=\"GundersonOdo2013p98\">{{cite book|author1=Lee Gunderson|author2=Dennis Murphy Odo|author3=Reginald D'Silva|title=ESL Literacy Instruction |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nak3AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA98 |year=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-05238-6|page=98}}</ref> A Midgan-Madiban has been deemed as polluting and therefore avoided as a taboo in the Somali society.<ref name=\"GundersonOdo2013p98\"/><ref name=\"Leonard2013p255\">{{cite book|author=Thomas M. Leonard|title=Encyclopedia of the Developing World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gc2NAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA255 |year=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-20508-9|page=255}}</ref><ref>Mohamed A. Eno and Abdi M. Kusow (2014), ''Racial and Caste Prejudice in Somalia'', Journal of Somali Studies, Iowa State University Press, Volume 1, Issue 2, pages 91-92, 95-96, 108-112</ref>\n\nUnder Somalia's military administration, some Madhiban were appointed to positions within the government to promote integration. The Madhiban have since obtained wider political representation. Their general social status has also improved with the expansion of urban centers.<ref name=\"Lewis\">{{cite book|last=Lewis|first=I.M.|title=Understanding Somalia and Somaliland: Culture, History, Society|year=2008|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=0231700849|pages=8}}</ref>\n\n==Description from 1890==\nIn 1890 [[\u00c9lis\u00e9e Reclus]], in his extensive work \"The Earth and its Inhabitants: AFRICA\" (Vol. IV, South and East Africa) described the Madhiban (Midgan) as follows: <blockquote>In still greater contempt are held the Midgans, called also Rami, that is to say \"Archers,\" who are universally regarded as the lowest of the low. They worship trees and snakes, and eat all the prohibited food, such as fish, fowl, eggs, hares, and gazelles. They are also daring hunters, fearlessly attacking the lion and the elephant, whom they pierce with their poisoned arrows. Like the Yebirs, the Midgans also practise medicine, and have the reputation of being extremely clever charlatans. According to the Somali legends, the lower castes are the issue of crossings between Abyssinian women and maleficent genii, while the Midgans are of still more degraded origin, their ancestors having been the slaves of these Abyssinian women.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/earthanditsinha01keangoog \"The Earth and its Inhabitants: AFRICA\", Vol. IV, South and East Africa]. By \u00c9lys\u00e9e Reclus. Edited by A.H. Keane <small>B.A.</small>, New York, D. Appleton and Company., 1890 (page 399).</ref>.</blockquote>\n\n==Law==\nUnder the 1951 UN convention, several legal proceedings have ruled that Midgan as a low caste in Somalia are \"akin to [[Dalit]]s or the untouchables in India\".<ref name=\"D\u00f6rschner2011p398\"/>\n\n==Cognate castes in Horn of Africa==\nThe Madhiban caste is not an exception limited to the Somali ethnic group, and equivalent cognate caste is found in numerous ethnic groups in [[Horn of Africa]] and [[East Africa]].<ref name=levine57/><ref name=\"Shack1964p50\"/> According to [[Donald N. Levine|Donald Levine]] \u2013 a professor of Sociology specializing in Ethiopian and Horn of Africa studies, similar caste groups in different languages and ethnic groups have been integral part of societies of this region.<ref name=levine57>{{cite book|author=Donald N. Levine|title=Greater Ethiopia: The Evolution of a Multiethnic Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NZHeBQAAQBAJ |date=10 December 2014|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-22967-6|pages=57, 169\u2013171}}</ref> These strata have featured all the defining characteristics of caste, states Levine, characteristics such as \"endogamy, hierarchy, status, concepts of pollution, restraints on commensality, a traditional occupation and membership by birth\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Donald N. Levine|title=Greater Ethiopia: The Evolution of a Multiethnic Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NZHeBQAAQBAJ |date=10 December 2014|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-22967-6|pages=57\u201358}}</ref> In east Ethiopia ethnic groups, such as the [[Oromo people]], cognates to Somali castes have been recorded in 16th century texts, states Cornelius Jaenen.<ref>Cornelius J. Jaenen (1956), \n''The Galla or Oromo of East  Ethiopia '', Southwestern Journal of Anthropology, University of Chicago Press, Vol. 12, No. 2 (Summer, 1956), pages 171-190</ref> The table below illustrate some alternate terms for castes mirroring the Madhiban in other ethnic groups that share this region with the Somali people.<ref name=\"Levine2014p196\">{{cite book|author=Donald N. Levine|title=Greater Ethiopia: The Evolution of a Multiethnic Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NZHeBQAAQBAJ |date=10 December 2014|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-22967-6|pages=195\u2013196}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Castes equivalent to Madhiban in Horn of Africa\n! Ethnic group\n! Caste name<ref name=\"Levine2014p196\"/><ref>{{cite book|author=Sa\u00efd Amir Arjomand|title=Social Theory and Regional Studies in the Global Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nzSlAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA229|year=2014|publisher=State University of New York Press|isbn=978-1-4384-5161-9|pages=229\u2013237}}</ref>\n! Occupation\n|-\n! style=\"background: #00cc00;\" | Somali\n| style=\"background: #00cc00;\" | Midgan, Madhiban || hunters, tanners\n|-\n! [[Amhara people]]\n| Weyto, Faqi\n| hunters, tanners\n|-\n! [[Argobba people]]\n| Faqin\n| tanners\n|-\n! [[Borana people]]\n| Watta\n| hunters, tanners, potters, foragers\n|-\n! [[Gurage people]]\n| Fuga\n| hunters,<ref name=\"Shack1964p50\">{{cite journal | last=Shack | first=William A. | title=54. Notes on Occupational Castes Among the Gurage of South-West Ethiopia | journal=Man | publisher=Royal Anthropological Institute of Great Britain and Ireland | volume=64 | year=1964 | pages=50\u201352 | doi=10.2307/2797801 }}</ref> woodworkers\n|-\n! [[Janjero people]]\n| Fuga\n| hunters, potters, tanners\n|-\n! [[Kafa language|Kefa people]]\n| Manjo\n| hunters, guards\n|-\n! [[Qemant people|Kimant people]]\n| Arabinya\n| tanners\n|-\n! [[She people (Africa)|She people]]\n| Kwayeju\n| hunters\n|-\n! [[Sidama people]]\n| Awacho\n| tanners\n|}\n\n==Notable Madhiban==\n*[[Maryam Mursal]]\n\n==In America==\nIn 2009, the [[Minneapolis Police Department]] of [[Minneapolis, Minnesota]], reported that \"Madhibaan with Attitude\" was one of several Somali gangs active in the city.<ref>[https://www.cbsnews.com/news/rise-of-somali-gangs-plagues-minneapolis/ Rise of Somali Gangs Plagues Minneapolis], Associated Press (July 20, 2009).</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*Hassan Ali Jama, ''Who cares about Somalia'', (Verlag Hans Schiler: 2005)\n*I.M. Lewis, ''A pastoral democracy'', (James Currey Publishers: 1999)\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.jstor.org/stable/25653242 New Arabic Documents from Somalia], B.W. Andrzejewski, I.M. Lewis and R.S. O'Fahey (1994) \u2013 mention of Midgans in early Arabic documents\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Somalia}}\n{{Ethnic groups in Ethiopia}}\n{{Ethnic groups in Kenya}}\n{{Ethnic groups in Djibouti}}\n\n{{Somali clans}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Somali People}}\n[[Category:Cushitic-speaking peoples]]\n[[Category:Ethnic Somali people| ]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Somalia| ]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Kenya]]\n[[Category:Castes]]\n[[Category:Muslim communities in Africa]]\n", "name_user": "Abtiodon", "label": "safe", "comment": "I changed the article because it was out of date and racist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Madhiban"}
{"title_page": "Tuckpointing", "text_new": "{{for|the process of renewing the external part of mortar joints|Repointing}}\n \n[[Image:Tuck pointing Westminster.jpg|thumb|Brickwork of [[10 Downing Street]], showing fine white fillets in carefully matched dark mortar]]'''Tuckpointing''' (also called tuck pointing or tuck-pointing) is a way of using two contrasting colors of [[Mortar (masonry)|mortar]] in the [[mortar joint]]s of [[brickwork]], with one color matching the bricks themselves to give an artificial impression that very fine joints have been made. In some parts of the United States and Canada, some confusion may result as the term is often used interchangeably with ''[[wikt:pointing|pointing]]'' (to correct defects or finish off joints in newly laid masonry) and ''[[repointing]]'' (to place wet mortar into cut or raked joints to repair weathered joints in old masonry).\n\n==History==\nThe tuckpointing method was developed in [[England]] in the late eighteenth century<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/real-estate/toronto/the-lost-art-of-tuckpointing-reborn-intoronto/article37802073/|title=The lost art of tuckpointing reborn in\u00a0Toronto\u200b|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> to imitate brickwork constructed using ''rubbed bricks'' (also ''rubbers'' and ''gauged bricks''), which were bricks of fine, red finish that were made slightly over sized, and, after firing, then were individually [[abrasive|abraded]] or cut, often by hand, to a precise size.<ref>{{cite book|last=Conway|first=Hazel |author2=Roenisch, Rowan  |title=Understanding architecture|publisher=Routledge|location=London|date=15 December 2004|page=119|isbn=978-0-415-32058-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Hunt|first=Roger|author2=Suhr, Marianne|authorlink2=Marianne Suhr|title=The Old House Handbook|publisher=Frances Lincoln|location=London|date=23 October 2008|page=[https://archive.org/details/oldhousehandbook0000hunt/page/51 51]|isbn=978-0-7112-2772-9|url=https://archive.org/details/oldhousehandbook0000hunt/page/51}}</ref> When laid with white [[lime mortar]], a neat finish of red brick contrasting with very fine white joints was obtained. Tuckpointing was a way of achieving a similar effect using cheap, drubbed bricks: these were laid in a mortar of a matching color (initially red, but later, blue-black bricks and mortar were occasionally used) and a fine [[wikt:fillet|fillet]] of white material, usually  pipe clay or putty, pushed into the joints before the mortar set.<ref>[http://www.defence-estates.mod.uk/publications/historic_buildings/historic_buildings/PDF_8111/Technical%204%2001.pdf Walls, repointing brickwork] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071019225719/http://www.defence-estates.mod.uk/publications/historic_buildings/historic_buildings/PDF_8111/Technical%204%2001.pdf |date=2007-10-19 }} Ministry of Defence (Defence Estates), Sutton Coldfield, England, accessed 2007-10-17</ref> The term t''uckpointing'' derives from an earlier, less sophisticated technique that was used with very uneven bricks: a thin line, called a ''[[wikt:tuck|tuck]]'', was drawn in the flush-faced mortar, but left unfilled, to give the impression of well-formed brickwork.{{citation needed|reason=The OED says protruding, not incised|date=July 2012}}\n\n\n==Tuckpointing tools==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=April 2020}}\n{{copyedit|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:Tuck pointing on The Elms, 18th Century house in Acton - geograph.org.uk - 251637.jpg|thumb|Here red mortar is used. The white fillets are laid out at regular spacing, which does not always coincide with the rough spacing of the joints.]] \nProfessional \"tuckpointers\" use tuckpointing tools, which depending on the country and local trade terminology sometimes may be termed \"jointers\", \"tuck irons\"<ref name=\":0\" /> or \"tuckpointing irons\" (primarily in London where the trade originated).\n\nTuckpointing tools were originally made from [[Wrought_iron|wrought iron]] by [[Blacksmith|blacksmiths]] in England during the 18th century.  Modern tuckpointing tools are constructed from hardened [[tool steel]]. Tuckpointing tools typically have a wooden or synthetic handle that is attached to the tool surface by a metal [[ferrule]]. The tool surface itself has a sharp-pointed front and a flat, beaded or grooved base; the sharp point aids the user in smoothing the tuckpointed line. This is similar in principle to the pointed floats used by concrete finishers to smooth out a surface.\n\nThe thickness and width of a tuckpointing tool is variable, with common measurements ranging from 1 mm to 14 mm. The thickness and width of these tools are heavily dependent upon the mason's personal preference and the type of brick or stonework that they are tuckpointing. Wider tools are often used when tuckpointing stonework.\n\nThere are many different types of tuckpointing tools now available:\n\"Standard Tuckpointing Tools (flat bottomed)\",\n\"Square Beaded Tuckpointing Tool\",\n\"Round Beaded Tuckpointing Tools\", \n\"Stubnose and Longnose Tuckpointing tools\", and also rarer\n\"Rounded Corner Tuckpointing Tools\".\n\nStandard or flat bottomed tuckpointing tools were once the most commonly used tuckpointing tools, primarily because of the ease at which they could be manufactured by early blacksmiths. Standard tuckpointing tools are very versatile and can be used for a variety of different jobs ranging from very fine detail work up to wide stone tuckpointing work.\n\nTuckpointing tools are sometimes \"beaded\". First, beaded tuckpointing tools were crude instruments made by blacksmiths by hitting a rounded leading edged hammer against a red hot tuckpointing iron. This process has since been refined, and now a small rounded or square fillet is \"ground\" into the flat of the tuckpointing tool that comes into contact with the \"perps\" or \"lines\" in the brickwork. In bricklaying terms, the \"perps\" are the gaps between the bricks in which mortar runs in the vertical direction, perpendicular to the ends<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irishtechnews.ie/robots-podcast-hadrian-bricklaying-robot-with-mark-pivac/|title=Robots podcast: Hadrian bricklaying robot, with Mark Pivac|last=Cocking|first=Simon|date=2017-03-23|website=Irishtechnews.ie|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>. \"Lines\" run in the horizontal direction.\n\nThe lengths of tools again vary based upon personal preferences, but the most common lengths are usually between 7.5 and 12.5 cm. However, masons and bricklayers sometimes need tuckpointing tools which are much shorter or much longer. Shorter tools help the worker access hard to reach spots, like under a window or in a corner. These shorter tuckpointing tools are referred to as \"stubnose\" tools, while their longer counterparts are known as \"longnose\" tools. They are available in many different beaded or grooved profiles.\n\nSquare beaded tuckpointing tools are available in 4 mm, 5 mm, 6 mm, 8 mm, 10 mm, 12 mm, and 13 mm wide ground square profiles. Round beaded tuckpointing tools are available in 5 mm, 6 mm, 8 mm, 10 mm, and 12 mm ground round profiles.\n\n\"Rounded Corner Tuckpointing Tools\" are curved; instead of a flat bottom, the tool has a curved bottom surface which helps in applying lime putty to rounded bricks. \n\nThe process of tuckpointing requires that the excess lime putty is \"cut\" away from the fine tuckpointed line. This is performed using a Frenchmen<ref name=\":0\" /> knife or a double Frenchmen knife. A Frenchmen knife is a type of knife with a small sharp bent tip that allows the lime putty to be cut when guided along the tuckpointed line with a tuckpointer's straight edge. A double Frenchmen knife works by cutting both top and bottom tuckpointed fine lines in one pass, making the process quicker. Double Frenchmen knives can be adjusted to match the width of the fine tuckpointed lines.\n\nTuckpointing is a fairly rare but not forgotten trade. Many historic homes with classic [[Italianate architecture]] like the Werribee Mansion at [[Werribee Park]], in Victoria, Australia west of Melbourne, are great examples of recent tuckpointing which display the contrast between the tuckpointed white lines in the mortar between the bluestone architecture.\n\n==References==\n<references />\nhttps://www.masonrymagazine.com/blog/2008/09/01/tuckpointing-and-repointing-tools/\n{{Stonemasonry}}\n\n[[Category:Masonry]]\n[[Category:Bricks]]\n[[Category:Stonemasonry]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the process of renewing the external part of mortar joints|Repointing}}\n \n[[Image:Tuck pointing Westminster.jpg|thumb|Brickwork of [[10 Downing Street]], showing fine white fillets in carefully matched dark mortar]]'''Tuckpointing''' (also called tuck pointing or tuck-pointing) is a way of using two contrasting colours of [[Mortar (masonry)|mortar]] in the [[mortar joint]]s of [[brickwork]], with one colour matching the bricks themselves to give an artificial impression that very fine joints have been made. In some parts of the United States and Canada, some confusion may result as the term is often used interchangeably with ''[[wikt:pointing|pointing]]'' (to correct defects or finish off joints in newly laid masonry) and ''[[repointing]]'' (to place wet mortar into cut or raked joints to repair weathered joints in old masonry).\n\n==History==\nThe tuckpointing method was developed in [[England]] in the late eighteenth century<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/real-estate/toronto/the-lost-art-of-tuckpointing-reborn-intoronto/article37802073/|title=The lost art of tuckpointing reborn in\u00a0Toronto\u200b|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> to imitate brickwork constructed using ''rubbed bricks'' (also ''rubbers'' and ''gauged bricks''), which were bricks of fine, red finish that were made slightly oversized, and, after firing, then were individually [[abrasive|abraded]] or cut, often by hand, to a precise size.<ref>{{cite book|last=Conway|first=Hazel |author2=Roenisch, Rowan  |title=Understanding architecture|publisher=Routledge|location=London|date=15 December 2004|page=119|isbn=978-0-415-32058-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Hunt|first=Roger|author2=Suhr, Marianne|authorlink2=Marianne Suhr|title=The Old House Handbook|publisher=Frances Lincoln|location=London|date=23 October 2008|page=[https://archive.org/details/oldhousehandbook0000hunt/page/51 51]|isbn=978-0-7112-2772-9|url=https://archive.org/details/oldhousehandbook0000hunt/page/51}}</ref> When laid with white [[lime mortar]], a neat finish of red brick contrasting with very fine white joints was obtained. Tuckpointing was a way of achieving a similar effect using cheap, unrubbed bricks: these were laid in a mortar of a matching colour (initially red, but later, blue-black bricks and mortar were occasionally used) and a fine [[wikt:fillet|fillet]] of white material, usually  pipeclay or putty, pushed into the joints before the mortar set.<ref>[http://www.defence-estates.mod.uk/publications/historic_buildings/historic_buildings/PDF_8111/Technical%204%2001.pdf Walls, repointing brickwork] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071019225719/http://www.defence-estates.mod.uk/publications/historic_buildings/historic_buildings/PDF_8111/Technical%204%2001.pdf |date=2007-10-19 }} Ministry of Defence (Defence Estates), Sutton Coldfield, England, accessed 2007-10-17</ref> The term ''tuckpointing'' derives from an earlier, less sophisticated technique that was used with very uneven bricks: a thin line, called a ''[[wikt:tuck|tuck]]'', was drawn in the flush-faced mortar, but left unfilled, to give the impression of well-formed brickwork.{{citation needed|reason=The OED says protruding, not incised|date=July 2012}}\n\n==Tuckpointing tools==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=April 2020}}\n{{copyedit|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:Tuck pointing on The Elms, 18th Century house in Acton - geograph.org.uk - 251637.jpg|thumb|Here red mortar is used. The white fillets are laid out at regular spacing, which does not always coincide with the rough spacing of the joints.]] \nProfessional \"tuckpointers\" use tuckpointing tools, which depending on the country and local trade terminology sometimes may be termed \"jointers\", \"tuck irons\"<ref name=\":0\" /> or \"tuckpointing irons\" (primarily in London where the trade originated).\n\nTuckpointing tools were originally made from [[Wrought_iron|wrought iron]] by [[Blacksmith|blacksmiths]] in England during the 18th century.  Modern tuckpointing tools are constructed from hardened [[tool steel]]. Tuckpointing tools typically have a wooden or synthetic handle that is attached to the tool surface by a metal [[ferrule]]. The tool surface itself has a sharp-pointed front and a flat, beaded or grooved base; the sharp point aids the user in smoothing the tuckpointed line. This is similar in principle to the pointed floats used by concrete finishers to smooth out a surface.\n\nThe thickness and width of a tuckpointing tool is variable, with common measurements ranging from 1 mm to 14 mm. The thickness and width of these tools are heavily dependent upon the mason's personal preference and the type of brick or stonework that they are tuckpointing. Wider tools are often used when tuckpointing stonework.\n\nThere are many different types of tuckpointing tools now available:\n\"Standard Tuckpointing Tools (flat bottomed)\",\n\"Square Beaded Tuckpointing Tool\",\n\"Round Beaded Tuckpointing Tools\", \n\"Stubnose and Longnose Tuckpointing tools\", and also rarer\n\"Rounded Corner Tuckpointing Tools\".\n\nStandard or flat bottomed tuckpointing tools were once the most commonly used tuckpointing tools, primarily because of the ease at which they could be manufactured by early blacksmiths. Standard tuckpointing tools are very versatile and can be used for a variety of different jobs ranging from very fine detail work up to wide stone tuckpointing work.\n\nTuckpointing tools are sometimes \"beaded\". First, beaded tuckpointing tools were crude instruments made by blacksmiths by hitting a rounded leading edged hammer against a red hot tuckpointing iron. This process has since been refined, and now a small rounded or square fillet is \"ground\" into the flat of the tuckpointing tool that comes into contact with the \"perps\" or \"lines\" in the brickwork. In bricklaying terms, the \"perps\" are the gaps between the bricks in which mortar runs in the vertical direction, perpendicular to the ends<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irishtechnews.ie/robots-podcast-hadrian-bricklaying-robot-with-mark-pivac/|title=Robots podcast: Hadrian bricklaying robot, with Mark Pivac|last=Cocking|first=Simon|date=2017-03-23|website=Irishtechnews.ie|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>. \"Lines\" run in the horizontal direction.\n\nThe lengths of tools again vary based upon personal preferences, but the most common lengths are usually between 7.5 and 12.5 cm. However, masons and bricklayers sometimes need tuckpointing tools which are much shorter or much longer. Shorter tools help the worker access hard to reach spots, like under a window or in a corner. These shorter tuckpointing tools are referred to as \"stubnose\" tools, while their longer counterparts are known as \"longnose\" tools. They are available in many different beaded or grooved profiles.\n\nSquare beaded tuckpointing tools are available in 4 mm, 5 mm, 6 mm, 8 mm, 10 mm, 12 mm, and 13 mm wide ground square profiles. Round beaded tuckpointing tools are available in 5 mm, 6 mm, 8 mm, 10 mm, and 12 mm ground round profiles.\n\n\"Rounded Corner Tuckpointing Tools\" are curved; instead of a flat bottom, the tool has a curved bottom surface which helps in applying lime putty to rounded bricks. \n\nThe process of tuckpointing requires that the excess lime putty is \"cut\" away from the fine tuckpointed line. This is performed using a Frenchmen<ref name=\":0\" /> knife or a double Frenchmen knife. A Frenchmen knife is a type of knife with a small sharp bent tip that allows the lime putty to be cut when guided along the tuckpointed line with a tuckpointer's straight edge. A double Frenchmen knife works by cutting both top and bottom tuckpointed fine lines in one pass, making the process quicker. Double Frenchmen knives can be adjusted to match the width of the fine tuckpointed lines.\n\nTuckpointing is a fairly rare but not forgotten trade. Many historic homes with classic [[Italianate architecture]] like the Werribee Mansion at [[Werribee Park]], in Victoria, Australia west of Melbourne, are great examples of recent tuckpointing which display the contrast between the tuckpointed white lines in the mortar between the bluestone architecture.\n\n==References==\n<references />\nhttps://www.masonrymagazine.com/blog/2008/09/01/tuckpointing-and-repointing-tools/\n{{Stonemasonry}}\n\n[[Category:Masonry]]\n[[Category:Bricks]]\n[[Category:Stonemasonry]]\n", "name_user": "Muhammadalishahid856", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tuckpointing"}
{"title_page": "Vietnam mouse-deer", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Small hoofed mammal 'lost' until November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name          = Vietnam mouse-deer\n| image         =\n| status        = DD\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref    =<ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn|author=Timmins, R.J.|author2=Duckworth, J.W.|author3=Meijaard, E.|last-author-amp=yes|year=2008|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/136360/0|title=''Tragulus versicolor''|access-date=29 March 2009|ref=harv}} Database entry includes a brief justification of why this species is of data deficient.</ref>\n| genus         = Tragulus\n| species       = versicolor\n| authority     = [[Oldfield Thomas|Thomas]], 1910\n| synonyms      = \n| range_map = Tragulus versicolor.png\n| range_map_caption = Range of the Vietnam mouse deer (2008)<ref name=iucn/>\n}}\n\nThe '''Vietnam mouse-deer''' (''Tragulus versicolor''), also known as the '''silver-backed chevrotain''', is an [[even-toed ungulate]] in the family [[Tragulidae]] known only from [[Vietnam]]. It was first [[Scientific description|described]] by British zoologist [[Oldfield Thomas]] in 1910, who procured four specimens from [[Nha Trang]] in [[Annam (French protectorate)|Annam]]. Sighted only thrice in the wild, little is known about the distribution and ecology of this mouse-deer. After 1910, the Vietnam mouse-deer was reported next in 1990 near Dak Rong and Buon Luoi in the [[Gia Lai Province]]. With increasing hunting pressure, habitat loss due to deforestation and no more reports of the species in the wild, the mouse-deer was feared to have gone extinct. The [[IUCN]] listed the species as [[Data Deficient]] in 2008. In 2019, a study confirmed the presence of the Vietnam mouse-deer in dry low-lying forests of southern Vietnam with [[camera trap]] evidence. This mouse-deer is characterised by a rough coat with a strange double-tone coloration unseen in other chevrotains; the front part of the body is reddish brown and contrasts strongly with the greyish posterior. It has big reddish brown ears, white and dark reddish brown marks on the throat.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe Vietnam mouse-deer was first [[Scientific description|described]] by British zoologist [[Oldfield Thomas]] in 1910 by the [[Binomial nomenclature|name]] ''Tragulus versicolor''.<ref name=thomas>{{cite journal |last=Thomas |first=Oldfield |authorlink=Oldfield Thomas|year=1910 |journal=The Annals and Magazine of Natural History |series=8 |volume=5 |page=535 |issue=25\u201330 |title=''Tragulus versicolor'' |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/54587#page/571/mode/1up}}</ref><ref name=msw3>{{MSW3|page=650|id=14200183}}</ref> In the past this mouse-deer was generally treated as a [[subspecies]] of the [[greater mouse-deer]] (''T.&nbsp;napu''), though it more closely resembles the [[lesser mouse-deer]] (''T.&nbsp;kanchil''). In a taxonomic revision in 2004, the Vietnam mouse-deer was identified as an independent species in ''Tragulus''.<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Erik |last1=Meijaard |first2=C.P. |last2=Groves |year=2004 |url=http://zmmu.msu.ru/rjt/articles/ther3_1%2009_13%20Kuznez_Borisenko.pdf |title=A taxonomic revision of the ''Tragulus'' mouse-deer (Artiodactyla) |journal=Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society |volume=140 |issue=1 |pages=63\u2013102 |doi=10.1111/j.1096-3642.2004.00091.x}}</ref>\n\n==Status and sightings==\nInformation on the distribution and ecology of this mouse-deer is scarce; it is [[endemic]] to Vietnam and has been sighted only thrice in the wild. The four specimens obtained by Thomas were from [[Nha Trang]] ({{Coord|12|15|N|109|10|E}}) in [[Annam (French protectorate)|Annam]] on the southern coast of Vietnam; this need not be the original location for the species, as the specimens could have been traded from elsewhere.<ref name=iucn/> The mouse-deer was not reported for another 80 years until a Vietnamese-Russian expedition procured an adult male specimen from local hunters near Dak Rong and Buon Luoi in the [[Gia Lai Province]]. This specimen, initially assumed to be a [[Java mouse-deer]] (''T. javanicus''), was deposited in the [[Zoological Museum of Moscow University]]. A reexamination in 2004 identified the specimen as a Vietnam mouse-deer, noting its strange coloration compared to other chevrotains.<ref name=new2004>{{cite journal |last1=Kuznetsov |first1=G. V. |last2=Borissenko |first2=A. V. |title=A new record of ''Tragulus versicolor'' (Artiodactyla, Tragulidae) from Vietnam, and its sympatric occurrence with ''T. kanchil'' |journal=Russian Journal of Theriology |date=2004 |issue=3 |pages=9-13 |doi=10.15298/rusjtheriol.3.1.03}}</ref> Follow-up surveys indicated that heavy deforestation and hunting pressure in the area had emerged as major threats to chevrotains in the area, but no significant measures were taken to assess the status of the Vietnam mouse-deer. With severe risks to its survival and no new specimens discovered, scientists feared the Vietnam mouse-deer might have gone extinct.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Meijaard |first1=E. |last2=Groves |first2=C.P. |title=Recent study identifies the possible existence of a forgotten species |journal=Oryx |date=2004 |volume=38 |pages=132-133}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Meijaard |first1=E. |last2=Borissenko |first2=A.V. |last3=Kuznetsov |first3=G.V. |title=Rediscovery of ''Tragulus versicolor'', the silver-backed chevrotain |journal=Oryx |date=2004 |volume=38 |pages=254-255}}</ref><ref name=\"ng\">{{cite news |last1=Leahy |first1=S. |title=Fanged mouse-deer identified after vanishing for a generation |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2019/11/silver-backed-chevrotain-mouse-deer-reappears-vietnam/ |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=National Geographic |date=11 November 2019}}</ref> The [[IUCN]], in lack of survey data or ecological cues from which the status and population trend could be reliably assessed, listed the species as [[Data Deficient]] in 2008.<ref name=iucn/> The Vietnam mouse-deer was listed among the 25&nbsp;\"most wanted lost\" species that are the focus of Global Wildlife Conservation's Search for Lost Species initiative.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.lostspecies.org |title=The Search for Lost Species |date= |website=Global Wildlife Conservation |access-date=10 July 2017}}</ref> \n\nAfter nearly 30 years since the last sighting, a study published in 2019 by researchers associated with the Global Wildlife Conservation confirmed the presence of Vietnam mouse-deer in dry low-lying forests on the southern coast of Vietnam. The researchers had begun with interviews of local people, some of whom suggested the presence of two types of chevrotain in the area; all interviewees agreed that chevrotain populations had declined over the years in the region due to hunting. [[Camera trap]]s were set up in areas from where grey chevrotain had been reported; the researchers were successful in capturing images of Vietnam mouse-deer, easily identifiable by their characteristic double-tone coloration and throat markings. The researchers aim to further study the size and stability of the populations.<ref name=nguyen>{{cite journal |last1=Nguyen |first1=A. |last2=Tran |first2=V.B. |last3=Hoang |first3=D.M. |last4=Nguyen |first4=T.A.M. |last5=Nguyen |first5=D.T. |last6=Tran |first6=V.T. |last7=Long |first7=B. |last8=Meijaard |first8=E. |last9=Holland |first9=J. |last10=Wilting |first10=A. |last11=Tilker |first11=A. |title=Camera-trap evidence that the silver-backed chevrotain ''Tragulus versicolor'' remains in the wild in Vietnam |journal=Nature Ecology & Evolution |date=2019 |volume=3 |issue=12 |pages=1650\u20131654 |doi=10.1038/s41559-019-1027-7}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Iati |first1=M. |title=A tiny \u2018deer\u2019 was feared extinct. Scientists just photographed it for the first time in a generation. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/science/2019/11/12/tiny-deer-was-feared-extinct-scientists-just-photographed-it-first-time-generation/ |date=12 November 2019 |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Preston |first1=E. |title=This elusive creature wasn't seen for nearly 30 years. Then it appeared on camera. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/11/science/vietnam-silver-backed-chevrotain.html |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=The New York Times |date=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Ecology and habitat==\nCamera trap evidence from the 2019 study suggests that Vietnam mouse-deer are [[diurnality|diurnal]] (active mainly during the day), and stay solitary or form pairs.<ref name=nguyen/> The locality where the 1990 specimen was obtained was a low-lying area of [[semi-deciduous]] tropical forest; several lesser mouse-deer specimens were found in the same area, suggesting [[sympatry]].<ref name=new2004/> The 2019 study observed the Vietnam mouse-deer in dry lowland forest near the southern coast of Vietnam.<ref name=nguyen/>\n\n==Physical description==\nIn his 1910 account, Thomas described the Vietnam mouse-deer as having a rough coat, big reddish brown ears, white and dark reddish brown marks on the throat. He noted the sharp contrast between the reddish brown colour of the front part of the body up to the shoulders, and the grey posterior separated by a line of buff from the white underparts\u2014such stark variation is not observed in other chevrotains. The tail, grey in the upper part and white below, becomes more reddish brown toward the tip, which is white. Per his measurements, the head-and-body length is around {{convert|48|cm|in|abbr=on}} and the tail is {{convert|5|cm|in|abbr=on}} long.<ref name=thomas/> Examiners of the 1990 specimen noted its [[shabrack]]-like coat with dense fur on the back and white hair tips. A prominent silver line runs down the back, hence the name \"silver-backed\". The neck and shoulders are more brown with less dense fur; unlike the lesser mouse-deer the fur on the neck is coarser and less prickly. The Vietnam mouse-deer lacks the dark markings along the flanks and the middle portion of the underparts visible in the lesser mouse-deer.<ref name=new2004/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Saplakoglu |first1=Y. |title=A tiny species that looks part-deer, part-mouse was missing for nearly 30 years. Scientists just found it|url=https://www.livescience.com/lost-silver-backed-chevrotain-captured-photos.html |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=Live Science |date=11 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{Portal-inline|Mammals}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Artiodactyla|R.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q966649}}\n\n[[Category:Tragulus]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1910]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Small hoofed mammal 'lost' until November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name          = Vietnam mouse-deer\n| image         =\n| status        = DD\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref    =<ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn|author=Timmins, R.J.|author2=Duckworth, J.W.|author3=Meijaard, E.|last-author-amp=yes|year=2008|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/136360/0|title=''Tragulus versicolor''|access-date=29 March 2009|ref=harv}} Database entry includes a brief justification of why this species is of data deficient.</ref>\n| genus         = Tragulus\n| species       = versicolor\n| authority     = [[Oldfield Thomas|Thomas]], 1910\n| synonyms      = \n| range_map = Tragulus versicolor.png\n| range_map_caption = Range of the Vietnam mouse deer (2008)<ref name=iucn/>\n}}\n\nThe '''Vietnam mouse-deer''' (''Tragulus versicolor''), also known as the '''silver-backed chevrotain''', is an [[even-toed ungulate]] in the family [[Tragulidae]] known only from [[Vietnam]]. It was first [[Scientific description|described]] by British zoologist [[Oldfield Thomas]] in 1910, who procured four specimens from [[Nha Trang]] in [[Annam (French protectorate)|Annam]]. Sighted only thrice in the wild, little is known about the distribution and ecology of this mouse-deer. After 1910, the Vietnam mouse-deer was reported next in 1990 near Dak Rong and Buon Luoi in the [[Gia Lai Province]]. With increasing hunting pressure, habitat loss due to deforestation and no more reports of the species in the wild, the mouse-deer was feared to have gone extinct. The [[IUCN]] listed the species as [[Data Deficient]] in 2008. In 2019, a study confirmed the presence of the Vietnam mouse-deer in dry low-lying forests of southern Vietnam with [[camera trap]] evidence. This mouse-deer is characterised by a rough coat with a strange double-tone colouration unseen in other chevrotains; the front part of the body is reddish brown and contrasts strongly with the greyish posterior. It has big reddish brown ears, white and dark reddish brown marks on the throat.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe Vietnam mouse-deer was first [[Scientific description|described]] by British zoologist [[Oldfield Thomas]] in 1910 by the [[Binomial nomenclature|name]] ''Tragulus versicolor''.<ref name=thomas>{{cite journal |last=Thomas |first=Oldfield |authorlink=Oldfield Thomas|year=1910 |journal=The Annals and Magazine of Natural History |series=8 |volume=5 |page=535 |issue=25\u201330 |title=''Tragulus versicolor'' |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/54587#page/571/mode/1up}}</ref><ref name=msw3>{{MSW3|page=650|id=14200183}}</ref> In the past this mouse-deer was generally treated as a [[subspecies]] of the [[greater mouse-deer]] (''T.&nbsp;napu''), though it more closely resembles the [[lesser mouse-deer]] (''T.&nbsp;kanchil''). In a taxonomic revision in 2004, the Vietnam mouse-deer was identified as an independent species in ''Tragulus''.<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Erik |last1=Meijaard |first2=C.P. |last2=Groves |year=2004 |url=http://zmmu.msu.ru/rjt/articles/ther3_1%2009_13%20Kuznez_Borisenko.pdf |title=A taxonomic revision of the ''Tragulus'' mouse-deer (Artiodactyla) |journal=Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society |volume=140 |issue=1 |pages=63\u2013102 |doi=10.1111/j.1096-3642.2004.00091.x}}</ref>\n\n==Status and sightings==\nInformation on the distribution and ecology of this mouse-deer is scarce; it is [[endemic]] to Vietnam and has been sighted only thrice in the wild. The four specimens obtained by Thomas were from [[Nha Trang]] ({{Coord|12|15|N|109|10|E}}) in [[Annam (French protectorate)|Annam]] on the southern coast of Vietnam; this need not be the original location for the species, as the specimens could have been traded from elsewhere.<ref name=iucn/> The mouse-deer was not reported for another 80 years until a Vietnamese-Russian expedition procured an adult male specimen from local hunters near Dak Rong and Buon Luoi in the [[Gia Lai Province]]. This specimen, initially assumed to be a [[Java mouse-deer]] (''T. javanicus''), was deposited in the [[Zoological Museum of Moscow University]]. A reexamination in 2004 identified the specimen as a Vietnam mouse-deer, noting its strange coloration compared to other chevrotains.<ref name=new2004>{{cite journal |last1=Kuznetsov |first1=G. V. |last2=Borissenko |first2=A. V. |title=A new record of ''Tragulus versicolor'' (Artiodactyla, Tragulidae) from Vietnam, and its sympatric occurrence with ''T. kanchil'' |journal=Russian Journal of Theriology |date=2004 |issue=3 |pages=9-13 |doi=10.15298/rusjtheriol.3.1.03}}</ref> Follow-up surveys indicated that heavy deforestation and hunting pressure in the area had emerged as major threats to chevrotains in the area, but no significant measures were taken to assess the status of the Vietnam mouse-deer. With severe risks to its survival and no new specimens discovered, scientists feared the Vietnam mouse-deer might have gone extinct.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Meijaard |first1=E. |last2=Groves |first2=C.P. |title=Recent study identifies the possible existence of a forgotten species |journal=Oryx |date=2004 |volume=38 |pages=132-133}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Meijaard |first1=E. |last2=Borissenko |first2=A.V. |last3=Kuznetsov |first3=G.V. |title=Rediscovery of ''Tragulus versicolor'', the silver-backed chevrotain |journal=Oryx |date=2004 |volume=38 |pages=254-255}}</ref><ref name=\"ng\">{{cite news |last1=Leahy |first1=S. |title=Fanged mouse-deer identified after vanishing for a generation |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2019/11/silver-backed-chevrotain-mouse-deer-reappears-vietnam/ |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=National Geographic |date=11 November 2019}}</ref> The [[IUCN]], in lack of survey data or ecological cues from which the status and population trend could be reliably assessed, listed the species as [[Data Deficient]] in 2008.<ref name=iucn/> The Vietnam mouse-deer was listed among the 25&nbsp;\"most wanted lost\" species that are the focus of Global Wildlife Conservation's Search for Lost Species initiative.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.lostspecies.org |title=The Search for Lost Species |date= |website=Global Wildlife Conservation |access-date=10 July 2017}}</ref> \n\nAfter nearly 30 years since the last sighting, a study published in 2019 by researchers associated with the Global Wildlife Conservation confirmed the presence of Vietnam mouse-deer in dry low-lying forests on the southern coast of Vietnam. The researchers had begun with interviews of local people, some of whom suggested the presence of two types of chevrotain in the area; all interviewees agreed that chevrotain populations had declined over the years in the region due to hunting. [[Camera trap]]s were set up in areas from where grey chevrotain had been reported; the researchers were successful in capturing images of Vietnam mouse-deer, easily identifiable by their characteristic double-tone coloration and throat markings. The researchers aim to further study the size and stability of the populations.<ref name=nguyen>{{cite journal |last1=Nguyen |first1=A. |last2=Tran |first2=V.B. |last3=Hoang |first3=D.M. |last4=Nguyen |first4=T.A.M. |last5=Nguyen |first5=D.T. |last6=Tran |first6=V.T. |last7=Long |first7=B. |last8=Meijaard |first8=E. |last9=Holland |first9=J. |last10=Wilting |first10=A. |last11=Tilker |first11=A. |title=Camera-trap evidence that the silver-backed chevrotain ''Tragulus versicolor'' remains in the wild in Vietnam |journal=Nature Ecology & Evolution |date=2019 |volume=3 |issue=12 |pages=1650\u20131654 |doi=10.1038/s41559-019-1027-7}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Iati |first1=M. |title=A tiny \u2018deer\u2019 was feared extinct. Scientists just photographed it for the first time in a generation. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/science/2019/11/12/tiny-deer-was-feared-extinct-scientists-just-photographed-it-first-time-generation/ |date=12 November 2019 |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Preston |first1=E. |title=This elusive creature wasn't seen for nearly 30 years. Then it appeared on camera. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/11/science/vietnam-silver-backed-chevrotain.html |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=The New York Times |date=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Ecology==\nCamera trap evidence from the 2019 study suggests that Vietnam mouse-deer are diurnal (active mainly during the day), and stay solitary or form pairs.<ref name=nguyen/> The locality where the 1990 specimen was obtained was a low-lying area of [[semi-deciduous]] tropical forest; several lesser mouse-deer specimens were found in the same area, suggesting [[sympatry]].<ref name=new2004/> The 2019 study observed the Vietnam mouse-deer in dry lowland forest near the southern coast of Vietnam.<ref name=nguyen/>\n\n==Physical description==\nIn his 1910 account, Thomas described the Vietnam mouse-deer as having a rough coat, big reddish brown ears, white and dark reddish brown marks on the throat. He noted the sharp contrast between the reddish brown colour of the front part of the body up to the shoulders, and the grey posterior separated by a line of buff from the white underparts\u2014such stark variation is not observed in other chevrotains. The tail, grey in the upper part and white below, becomes more reddish brown toward the tip, which is white. Per his measurements, the head-and-body length is around {{convert|48|cm|in|abbr=on}} and the tail is {{convert|5|cm|in|abbr=on}} long.<ref name=thomas/> Examiners of the 1990 specimen noted its [[shabrack]]-like coat with dense fur on the back and white hair tips. A prominent silver line runs down the back, hence the name \"silver-backed\". The neck and shoulders are more brown with less dense fur; unlike the lesser mouse-deer the fur on the neck is coarser and less prickly. The Vietnam mouse-deer lacks the dark markings along the flanks and the middle portion of the underparts visible in the lesser mouse-deer.<ref name=new2004/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Saplakoglu |first1=Y. |title=A tiny species that looks part-deer, part-mouse was missing for nearly 30 years. Scientists just found it|url=https://www.livescience.com/lost-silver-backed-chevrotain-captured-photos.html |accessdate=10 April 2020 |publisher=Live Science |date=11 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{Portal-inline|Mammals}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Artiodactyla|R.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q966649}}\n\n[[Category:Tragulus]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1910]]\n", "name_user": "Sainsf", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vietnam_mouse-deer"}
